"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418956","Home Office","false","2015-10-12","<p>The consultation on police funding arrangements closed on 15 September and the responses are being analysed. The Government will consider these responses carefully to determine what changes, if any, are required. At this stage final force-level allocations have not been set and will not be determined until we have completed our analysis. We will continue to engage with policing partners during this process and intend to provide information, including exemplifications of future allocations, as these develop.</p><p>Alongside the development of the new funding model, we are developing a Policy Equalities Statement which will set out how this work has been completed in compliance with the Public Sector Equality Duty.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","10336","2015-10-12T14:12:01.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418956/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418956/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418956/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-15","Police: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps she has taken to ensure that the ongoing police funding formula consultation contains an adequate equality impact assessment.","false","Biography information for Mike Kane","Wythenshawe and Sale East","Mike Kane","10335"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418957","Home Office","false","2015-10-12","<p>The consultation on police funding arrangements closed on 15 September and the responses are being analysed. The Government will consider these responses carefully to determine what changes, if any, are required. At this stage final force-level allocations have not been set and will not be determined until we have completed our analysis. We will continue to engage with policing partners during this process and intend to provide information, including exemplifications of future allocations, as these develop.</p><p>Alongside the development of the new funding model, we are developing a Policy Equalities Statement which will set out how this work has been completed in compliance with the Public Sector Equality Duty.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","10335","2015-10-12T14:12:02.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418957/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418957/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418957/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-15","Police: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will publish the exemptions requested by police and crime commissioners and chief constables in the ongoing police funding formula consultation; what progress has been made on that review; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mike Kane","Wythenshawe and Sale East","Mike Kane","10336"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418958","Home Office","false","2015-09-28","<p>The Government first announced the funding package for the London 2012 Olympic and Paralympic Games in March 2007 [HCDebs dated 15 March 2007- Hansard Column 450]. This included a preliminary estimate of £600 million for policing and wider security tasks. In addition, £238 million was set aside as contingency.</p><p>The final cost of policing and wider security for the London 2012 Olympic and Paralympic Games was £423 million and the final cost of venue security was £429 million. [WMS dated 16 July 2013- Hansard Column 71ws].</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2015-09-28T11:12:39.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418958/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418958/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418958/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-15","Olympic and Paralympic Games 2012: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate the Government made (a) before and (b) after 7 July 2005 of the likely security costs for the London 2012 Olympic and Paralympic Games.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","10239"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418959","Home Office","false","2015-09-17","<p>The Psychoactive Substances Bill, introducing a blanket ban on the supply of psychoactive substances, was introduced before the House of Commons on 21 July 2015.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-09-17T14:48:31.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418959/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418959/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418959/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-15","Drugs: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when she plans to bring forward legislative proposals on the regulation of legal highs.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","10261"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418960","Home Office","false","2015-09-18","<p>The Government introduced the Psychoactive Substances Bill before the House on 21 July 2015. This legislation, which makes the sale, import,distribution or manufacture of Psychoactive substances a criminal offence, will apply to both online and offline markets.</p><p>The National Crime Agency and the police routinely monitor the unlawful sales of psychoactive substances and take robust action to close UK-based websites where they are found to be committing offences under the Misuse of Drugs Act 1971. Considerable illegal activity also takes place on the internet outside of UK jurisdiction and we will continue to work with international partners to develop an effective response to the supply of controlled drugs and to react swiftly to emerging threats.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-09-18T10:01:00.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418960/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418960/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418960/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-15","Drugs: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department is taking to control the sale of legal highs on the internet.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","10262"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418961","House of Commons Commission","false","2015-10-12","<p>A late sitting can refer to either an occasion when the House sits beyond its likely scheduled rise (i.e. 10.30pm on Monday, 7.30pm on Tuesday and Wednesday, 5.30pm on Thursday); or whenever the House sits beyond 10.00pm.</p><p>Two types of payments are made to staff in order to support evening sittings, including late sittings: the Unsocial Hours Payment (UHP), an annual flat-rate allowance paid across the year to staff required to work to an unspecified time during evening sittings; and the Evening Additional Hours (EAH) payment which reflects the number of additional hours worked after 6pm, paid at a standard rate from 1800 to 2230 and at a higher rate after 2230. Additionally, in certain circumstances overtime may be paid to staff which may or may not be related to the House’s sitting hours. These payments are not reflected in this answer as the records do not indicate in which circumstances they were made to support late sittings. A late night taxi service is provided to staff who are required to work late; this service is only available after 2300.</p><p>Security staff are employed by the Metropolitan Police Service and are paid in accordance with their terms and conditions of employment.</p><p>The costs of UHP, EAH and the late night taxi service in each year since 2010–11 was as follows:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Unsocial Hours Allowance*</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Evening hours payment*</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Travel Costs</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total Cost</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010–2011</p></td><td><p>£373,409.48</p></td><td><p>£473,171.13</p></td><td><p>£376,892.69</p></td><td><p>£1,223,473.29</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011–2012</p></td><td><p>£345,556.57</p></td><td><p>£503,810.57</p></td><td><p>£369,859.62</p></td><td><p>£1,219,226.77</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012–2013</p></td><td><p>£334,516.90</p></td><td><p>£433,007.60</p></td><td><p>£264,314.70</p></td><td><p>£1,031,839.20</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013–2014</p></td><td><p>£333,091.84</p></td><td><p>£412,079.02</p></td><td><p>£239,546.70</p></td><td><p>£984,717.56</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014–2015</p></td><td><p>£367,756.14</p></td><td><p>£341,638.12</p></td><td><p>£141,814.10</p></td><td><p>£851,208.36</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£1,754,303.93</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£2,163,706.44</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£1,392,427.81</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£5,310,465.18</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>* Inclusive of NI and pension contributions</p><p>It is not possible meaningfully to equate these staffing costs related to evening sittings to an average overall cost per hour of late night sittings for two reasons: firstly, costs for other types of marginal expenditure related to late sittings, such as utilities charges, are not recorded separately; secondly, the staffing costs are paid to facilitate all sittings after 6.00pm, rather than “late” sittings specifically, whether defined as after 10.00pm or beyond the likely scheduled rise.</p>","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","10254","2015-10-12T16:41:55.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418961/answer","Biography information for Tom Brake","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418961/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418961/answer",,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2015-09-15","House of Commons: Working Hours","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for Carshalton and Wallington representing the House of Commons Commission, pursuant to the Answer of 14 September 2015 to Question 9407, what estimate the Commission has made of the cost of overtime payments to staff resulting from late sittings of the House in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","10253"
