The remaining hubs are due to roll out across England by March 2016. The New Anglia Growth Hub provides support to businesses in the Suffolk area and has helped over 3,000 businesses and created 450 jobs. Four hubs currently provide support to businesses in the East of England area.</p><p>And the New Anglia Local Enterprise Partnership has secured over £220m as part of their Growth Deal to help transform the economy of Norfolk and Suffolk. This money will fund a range of initiatives including road improvements, building new innovation centres and providing grants to help businesses grow.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","10187","2015-09-22T13:34:04.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418626/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418626/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418626/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-14","Small Businesses: Government Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps his Department is taking to support small businesses in (a) Suffolk, (b) the East of England and (c) England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Jo Churchill","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill","10150"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418627","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-17","<p>The Government is determined to devolve powers previously held in Whitehall to local areas. We are pleased that many business, shoppers and interested groups have taken this opportunity to share their views on giving local leaders the power to determine whether extended Sunday trading is right for their area. We are currently considering all the responses and will publish the Government’s response in due course.</p><p> </p><p />","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-09-17T14:23:17.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418627/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418627/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418627/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-14","Sunday Trading","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, when his Department plans to publish the results of its consultation on Sunday trading.","false","Biography information for Mr David Burrowes","Enfield, Southgate","Mr David Burrowes","10159"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418628","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-22","<p>The consultation closed on 16 September and the Department is currently in the process of analysing the responses. A full breakdown of the number of responses by category will be provided as part of the Government’s response to the consultation.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-09-22T13:35:26.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418628/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418628/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418628/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-14","Sunday Trading","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many responses have been received to the consultation on the devolution of Sunday trading laws from (a) small businesses, (b) large businesses, (c) trades unions, (d) faith groups, (e) individuals and (f) others.","false","Biography information for Mr David Burrowes","Enfield, Southgate","Mr David Burrowes","10160"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418629","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-22","<p /> <p>We expect to publish the results of the Family Test alongside the Government’s response to the consultation shortly.</p><p />","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-09-22T09:43:55.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418629/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418629/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418629/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-14","Sunday Trading","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, when the Government plans to publish a family impact assessment relating to the proposal to devolve and deregulate Sunday trading laws.","false","Biography information for Mr David Burrowes","Enfield, Southgate","Mr David Burrowes","10161"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418630","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-05","<p /> <p>In 2013 the Department for Business Innovation and Skills (BIS) commissioned the <em>International Comparative Performance of the UK Research Base</em> Report to understand how the UK compares with other nations in research terms. The report highlighted that the UK’s field-weighted citation impact was the highest of those countries included in the report, rising to 1.66 in 2012<sup><sup>[1]</sup></sup>, compared to the world average of 1.0.</p><p>All science capital spend is agreed as part of a wider allocations process, informed by information from Research Councils and other partner organisations, as well as by evidence provided in business cases for specific capital projects. In addition, the 2014 science capital consultation allowed stakeholders to provide feedback on the adequacy of capital research spending.</p><p>All capital projects undertake regular assurance reviews.</p><br /><p>[1] <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/performance-of-the-uk-research-base-international-comparison-2013" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/performance-of-the-uk-research-base-international-comparison-2013</a></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-10-05T12:13:04.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418630/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418630/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418630/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-14","Science: Capital Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 11 September 2015 to Question 8264, what reviews his Department conducted into the adequacy of capital research spending in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","10151"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418631","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-24","<p>The latest information published by UCAS showing the percentage of 18 year olds from the most disadvantaged areas in England who obtain a place at university, is shown in the table. The figures show that in 2014 the entry rate reached its highest ever level.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Entry rates of English 18 year olds from the most disadvantaged areas<sup>1</sup>.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="5"><p>Year of entry</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>2014</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Entry rate</p></td><td><p>14.0</p></td><td><p>15.0</p></td><td><p>15.1</p></td><td><p>16.4</p></td><td><p>18.2</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Source: UCAS end of cycle report 2014</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>1. Quintile 1 of the POLAR2 measure of disadvantage. This measure was developed by HEFCE and classifies small areas across the UK into five groups according to their level of young participation in HE. Each of these groups represents around 20 per cent of young people and is ranked from quintile 1 (areas with the lowest young participation rates, considered as the most disadvantaged) to quintile 5 (highest young participation rates, considered most advantaged).<br></p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-09-24T12:24:25.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418631/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418631/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418631/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-14","Universities: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 14 September 2015 to Question 9131, what estimate his Department has made of the proportion of admissions to university of students from low-income backgrounds in each of the last five years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","10167"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418632","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-23","<p /> <p>The processing of Freedom of Information (FOI) requests is part of staff responsibilities across the Department. The number of hours spent on this activity is not separately identified.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-09-23T10:03:12.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418632/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418632/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418632/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-14","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many hours his Department spent on processing freedom of information requests in each of the last 24 months.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","10216"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418633","Cabinet Office","false","2015-09-17","<p>This information is not collected by the Cabinet Office. Details of Ministers’ meetings with external organisations and overseas visits are published routinely.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","10168","2015-09-17T15:59:06.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418633/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418633/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418633/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-09-14","Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, on which dates cabinet ministers visited Scotland on official engagements between 8 May 2015 and 14 September 2015; whether any further such visits are planned to take place before 18 September 2015; and what the purpose was of each such visit.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","10169"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418634","Cabinet Office","false","2015-09-17","<p>This information is not collected by the Cabinet Office. Details of Ministers’ meetings with external organisations and overseas visits are published routinely.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","10169","2015-09-17T15:59:06.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418634/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418634/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418634/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-09-14","Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, on which dates cabinet ministers visited Scotland on official engagements between 8 May 2014 and 18 September 2014; and what the purpose was of each such visit.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","10168"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418635","Cabinet Office","false","2015-09-22","<p>The estimated cost of the central processing of FoI requests at the Cabinet Office is £381,760.89. This includes the costs associated with the central operational and legal teams coordinating and advising on FOI requests across the department. It does not include litigation costs or the costs outside the central team as handling FoI requests is part of other civil servants’ wider duties and the detailed information requested is not separately identifiable.</p><p> </p>","West Dorset","Mr Oliver Letwin",,"2015-09-22T16:55:42.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418635/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Letwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418635/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418635/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-09-14","Cabinet Office: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many hours his Department spent on processing freedom of information requests in each of the last 24 months.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","10217"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418636","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-17","<p>There are no plans to make changes to intermediary relief from Stamp Duty and Stamp Duty Reserve Tax.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Intermediary relief ensures that the UK equity market functions efficiently by preserving liquidity. Changes to intermediary relief would risk causing serious disruption to the market with implications both for companies’ funding costs and for London’s position as a global listing venue. Even a small restriction could be damaging by causing a change in behaviour, resulting in less tax revenue overall.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-09-17T15:18:19.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418636/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418636/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418636/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-14","Stamp Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he plans to change the definition of intermediary relief from stamp duty and stamp duty reserve tax.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","10117"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418637","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-17","<p>We do not hold figures for the proportion of turnover in UK equities that was liable to Stamp Duty Reserve Tax.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-09-17T15:09:47.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418637/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418637/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418637/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-14","Stamp Duty Reserve Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what proportion of the turnover in UK equities is liable for stamp duty reserve tax in each of the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","10118"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418638","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-21","<p>The Barnett Formula will be applied to the Department of Health’s Spending Review settlement in the usual way. This will be reflected in the Welsh Government’s allocations when the outcome of the Spending Review is published on 25 November.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-09-21T10:27:39.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418638/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418638/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418638/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-14","Public Expenditure: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what Barnett consequential will accrue to Wales as a result of the planned £8 billion annual expenditure on the NHS in England.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","10098"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418639","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-21","<p>The Chancellor has received no recent representations from the Welsh Government on this subject. In November 2013, the Government accepted the Silk Commission’s recommendation that Vehicle Excise Duty should not be devolved to Wales.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-09-21T10:28:51.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418639/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418639/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418639/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-14","Public Expenditure: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what representations he has received from the Welsh Government on devolving vehicle excise duty to Wales.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","10099"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418640","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-21","<p>The Chancellor of the Exchequer said in his Summer Budget statement that the Government will engage with the devolved administrations on the funding implications for them of the reforms to Vehicle Excise Duty. Those discussions are at an early stage.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-09-21T10:39:28.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418640/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418640/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418640/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-14","Public Expenditure: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what Barnett consequential will accrue to Wales as a result of the use of vehicle excise duty to fund expenditure on the Road Investment Fund in England.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","10100"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418641","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-21","<p>The Barnett Formula is updated at every Spending Review. In accordance with the Statement of Funding Policy, the Treasury consults as appropriate with the Devolved Administrations.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The St David’s Day Command Paper published in February made clear that we would introduce a funding floor at the Spending Review.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-09-21T10:37:52.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418641/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418641/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418641/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-14","Public Expenditure: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent representations he has received from the Welsh Government on the effect of the Barnett Formula on the level of funding Wales receives.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","10101"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418642","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-22","<p>I refer the hon Member to my answer of 11 September.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>No assessment has been made of the potential effect of proposed changes to tax credits and housing benefit in the Summer Budget 2015 on the number of abortions in the UK.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2015-09-22T13:17:59.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418642/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418642/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418642/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-14","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 11 September 2015 to Question 8088, if he will make it his policy to conduct an assessment of the potential effect of proposed changes to tax credits and housing benefit in the Summer Budget 2015 on the number of abortions in the UK.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","10109"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418643","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-21","<p>Ensuring an open and transparent working relationship between the Treasury and the OBR is supported by the jointly agreed Memorandum of Understanding (MoU), which the Treasury has always respected. This includes Section 23 of the MoU.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-09-21T10:40:39.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418643/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418643/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418643/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-14","Office for Budget Responsibility","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent assessment he has made of the extent to which his Department has adhered to section 23 of the memorandum of understanding between the Office for Budget Responsibility and his Department; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","10110"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418644","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-22","<p>The information requested could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-09-22T13:00:55.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418644/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418644/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418644/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-14","Income Tax: Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the number of people who will potentially lose their personal tax allowance as a result of the provisions set out in clause 24 of the Finance Bill 2015.","false","Biography information for Stephen McPartland","Stevenage","Stephen McPartland","10112"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418645","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-22","<p>It is assumed that the question refers to clause 24 of the Summer 2015 Finance Bill: relief for finance costs related to residential property businesses.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>To make the tax system fairer, the Government will restrict the amount of tax relief landlords can claim on property finance costs (such as mortgage interest or interest on loans to buy furnishings) to the basic rate of tax. This will ensure that landlords with the largest incomes no longer receive the most generous tax treatment. To give landlords time to adjust the Government will introduce this change over 4 years starting from April 2017.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The actual number of taxpayers affected will depend on behavioural changes and other economic factors.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-09-22T13:19:23.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418645/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418645/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418645/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-14","Income Tax: Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the number of lower rate income tax payers who will potentially be moved into the higher rate as a result of the provisions set out in clause 24 of the Finance Bill 2015.","false","Biography information for Stephen McPartland","Stevenage","Stephen McPartland","10113"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418646","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-18","<p>The government has taken a number of steps to promote financial inclusion and capability.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Following extensive government negotiations with the banking industry, the nine largest current account providers in the UK have committed to improve basic bank accounts. From January 2016 basic bank accounts will be truly fee-free, allowing people who don’t have a bank account, or who would struggle to get a standard account due to money problems, to manage their money with certainty and clarity.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Money Advice Service (MAS) is currently coordinating the development of a nationwide Financial Capability Strategy, with partners including representatives from the third sector, the financial services industry, regulators and educators.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Alongside the introduction of the pension freedoms in April 2015, the government committed to providing free, impartial guidance through Pension Wise, to help people make informed and confident decisions about how they use their defined contribution pension savings in retirement.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-09-18T08:56:20.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418646/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418646/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418646/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-14","Financial Services: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps the Government is taking to promote financial inclusion and capability.","false","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","10132"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418647","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-22","<p>The reopening of the UK Embassy in Tehran in August followed gradual expansion of our bilateral engagement with Iran over the last two years, allowing us to discuss a broad range of issues, including areas where we and Iran have sharply differing views.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The nuclear deal agreed in July will give the international community confidence in the peaceful nature of Iran’s nuclear programme, by imposing strict limits and inspections on its nuclear activity. If Iran completes the agreed actions on its nuclear programme, and nuclear related economic and financial sanctions on Iran are lifted, there will also be commercial opportunities for UK firms and indirect impacts on the UK economy, for example via global energy prices.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>However, the impact of the deal will be complex, and the impact of improved relations with Iran on the UK economy is therefore uncertain.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-09-22T10:01:01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418647/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418647/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418647/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-14","Foreign Relations: Iran","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make an assessment of the effect on the UK economy of improved relations with Iran.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","10204"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418648","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-21","<p>In accordance with Article 2(3) of Council Decision 2007/436/EC, Euratom of June 7<sup>th</sup> 2007 Member States retain, by way of collection costs, 25% of the amount of Traditional Own Resources, customs duties and sugar levies, which they collect.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-09-21T10:30:16.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418648/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418648/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418648/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-14","EU Budget: Contributions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what proportion of revenues assigned to the EU have been retained as UK national collection fees in each of the last five years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","10188"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418649","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-18","<p>The UK government has no exposure to Greece through its euro area loans. The Government has secured a deal that protects UK taxpayers from any risk from financing euro area bailouts now and in the future. This deal gives legal force to the commitment secured in 2010 that UK taxpayers would not be drawn into a euro area bailout.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>As a shareholder in the International Monetary Fund (IMF), the UK has an indirect exposure to Greece through the IMF’s overall lending. Our ultimate exposure to any IMF lending programme would be in line with our quota shareholding (around 4.5 per cent).</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-09-18T08:57:31.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418649/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418649/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418649/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-14","Economic Situation: Greece","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the potential fiscal effect on the UK of the government of Greece defaulting on its national debt.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","10194"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418650","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-17","<p>As the Barnett Formula is applied at a departmental level at Spending Reviews, it is not possible to disaggregate the application of the Barnett Formula to changes in individual programmes in the Department for Transport’s funding at either Spending Review 2010 or Spending Round 2013.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-09-17T15:07:16.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418650/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418650/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418650/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-14","Devolution: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much Barnett consequential funding the Government has provided to each of the devolved administrations as a result of changes in funding provided to the Department for Transport in each year since 2010-11 to date; and with which programmes such changes in funding were associated.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","10192"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418651","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-21","<p>At the Summer Budget 2015, the Government announced it will reduce the burden of inheritance tax for families by making it easier to pass on a home to direct descendants. Information about this measure is available at https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/inheritance-tax-main-residence-nil-rate-band-and-the-existing-nil-rate-band/inheritance-tax-main-residence-nil-rate-band-and-the-existing-nil-rate-band.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government keeps all taxes under review.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-09-21T10:31:57.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418651/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418651/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418651/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-14","Inheritance Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what plans his Department has to further reduce the level of inheritance tax on homes.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","10184"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418652","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-22","<p>The Treasury continuously monitors global economic developments, including those in China, and their impact on the UK as part of the normal process of policy development.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>As one of the most open trading economies in the world with a large financial sector, we have to recognise that the UK is not immune to the continued problems being experienced in the world economy.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We should not let this put us off. As the Chancellor recently said, while leading the UK’s Economic and Financial Dialogue with China this week, both countries: “have a shared commitment to laying the foundations for stronger, more productive economies that can weather periods of uncertainty. At the same time, we need to continue to pursue the longer-term reform challenges that both our governments are pursuing.”</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-09-22T13:14:32.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418652/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418652/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418652/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-14","Economic situation: China","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of China's economic slowdown on the UK economy.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","10185"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418653","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-22","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) is currently migrating hundreds of existing guidance manuals from its own website to GOV.UK. HMRC expects the changeover to be completed over the next few months. The department's priority has been moving existing manuals, but I am pleased to say that the Theatre Tax Relief Manual will be one of the first new manuals to be published on GOV.UK. In the interim, HMRC will shortly make available a temporary version via GOV.UK.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The theatre tax relief was introduced with effect from 1 September 2014. The regime provides relief for companies producing qualifying theatrical productions. There is a special unit within HMRC for the creative industries that regularly advise taxpayers on this relief and how to make claims.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-09-22T13:06:44.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418653/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418653/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418653/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-14","Theatre: Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when he plans to publish guidance notes on theatre tax relief.","false","Biography information for Nigel Huddleston","Mid Worcestershire","Nigel Huddleston","10156"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418654","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-22","<p>The government takes enforcement of the National Minimum Wage (NMW) very seriously. Anyone who feels they have been underpaid NMW should contact the Acas helpline on 0300 123 1100. HMRC review all complaints referred to them.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>HMRC maintain data of arrears recovered and actively pursue recovery through the civil courts where this is not paid. It is not government policy to provide in-year data as it has not been fully validated. HMRC record outstanding arrears being pursued for earlier years but this data cannot be broken down into individual years due to the way it is maintained. There are no plans to change the way HMRC’s data is maintained as it would be disproportionately expensive to do so.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-09-22T13:08:31.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418654/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418654/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418654/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-14","Social Services: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the Answer of 3 November 2014 to Question 211605, if he will instruct HM Revenue and Customs to keep data in a format that will enable provision of the statistics requested on the amount of arrears paid or not paid to workers.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","10153"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418655","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-22","<p>At the Summer Budget 2015, the Government announced it will reduce the burden of inheritance tax for families by making it easier to pass on a home to direct descendants. Information about this measure is available at https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/inheritance-tax-main-residence-nil-rate-band-and-the-existing-nil-rate-band/inheritance-tax-main-residence-nil-rate-band-and-the-existing-nil-rate-band.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government has sought to focus on the passing of homes to the next generation in the immediate family. This ensures that parents know they will be able to pass on the family home that they have worked hard for to the next generation without the worry of inheritance tax. Around 80% of estates with both a residence and an inheritance tax liability are expected to be in a position to benefit.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-09-22T13:10:11.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418655/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418655/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418655/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-14","Inheritance Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make it his policy to extend inheritance tax relief to (a) a mother and father and (b) a sibling or siblings living together in the family home.","false","Biography information for Bob Stewart","Beckenham","Bob Stewart","10162"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418656","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-18","<p>In accordance with OECD directives, the UK’s official development assistance budget will be used to cover support costs for Syrian refugees in the first twelve months of their stay. Funding arrangements to support the resettlement of Syrian refugees in future years will be considered as part of the 2015 spending review.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-09-18T09:04:40.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418656/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418656/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418656/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-14","Refugees: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what arrangements he is planning for the reallocation of his Department's funding for the resettlement of Syrian refugees within the UK.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","10210"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418657","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-18","<p>Processing Freedom of Information requests is an integral part of civil servants' responsibilities and so the number of hours spent on this activity is not separately identifiable.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-09-18T09:02:59.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418657/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418657/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418657/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-14","Treasury: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many hours his Department spent on processing freedom of information requests in each of the last 24 months.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","10232"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418658","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-09-17","<p>Tackling fly-tipping is a priority for the Government. As set out in our manifesto we will be giving councils the power to issue fixed penalty notices for small-scale fly-tipping as well as reviewing the existing fixed penalty notices for littering.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>These steps will build on other Government action to tackle fly-tipping, which has included; working with the Sentencing Council on its guideline for sentencing for environmental offences, which came into force on 1 July last year; making it easier for vehicles suspected of being involved in waste crime to be stopped, searched and seized; and continuing work in partnership with others through the Defra chaired National Fly-Tipping Prevention Group to promote and disseminate good practice in the prevention, reporting, investigation and clearance of fly-tipped waste.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2015-09-17T16:12:22.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418658/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418658/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418658/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-09-14","Fly-tipping","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what plans she has to counteract the rise in fly-tipping.","false","Biography information for Bob Stewart","Beckenham","Bob Stewart","10163"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418659","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-17","<p>The Government set out its assessment of the impacts of the policies in the Welfare Reform and Work Bill on 20th July. A link to the impact assessment is included.</p><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/documents/impact-assessments/IA15-006.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/documents/impact-assessments/IA15-006.pdf</a></p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","9965","2015-09-17T10:21:30.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418659/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418659/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418659/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-09-14","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the effect of reducing the benefit cap on (a) homelessness and (b) temporary accommodation costs borne by local authorities.","false","Biography information for Dawn Butler","Brent Central","Dawn Butler","10147"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418660","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-12","<p>Our £500 million investment in local authority and voluntary sector homelessness services has contributed to local authorities preventing 935,800 households from becoming homeless since 2010. Together with other Departments, we are considering the overall level of funding for local government through the Spending Review.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2015-10-12T14:33:14.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418660/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418660/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418660/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-09-14","Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what his policy is on the future of the homelessness prevention grant.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","10178"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418661","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-09-17","<p>Every part of the public sector has played a role in helping to lower the deficit. Councils, as independent employers, take local decisions about pay and consider how these decisions impact on their workforces. <br><br>At the Budget, the my rt. hon. Friend, the Chancellor of the Exchequer (George Osborne) announced the introduction of a new National Living Wage of over £9 by 2020. The National Living Wage is expected to benefit around 6 million low paid people across the country.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2015-09-17T12:39:05.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418661/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418661/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418661/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-09-14","Local Government: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the effect of the public sector pay freeze on the recruitment and retention of staff by local authorities.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","10140"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418662","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-09-16","<p>The Department does not record this information.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2015-09-16T15:58:18.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418662/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418662/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418662/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-09-14","Department for Communities and Local Government: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many hours his Department spent on processing freedom of information requests in each of the last 24 months.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","10218"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418663","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-09-21","<p>The Department does not hold information detailing the total hours spent on processing freedom of information requests. However, there are currently three full time employees at the Department whose primary function is to ‘oversee, respond to or co­ordinate obligations’ under the Freedom of Information Act.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-09-21T14:02:23.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418663/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418663/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418663/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-09-14","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many hours his Department spent on processing freedom of information requests in each of the last 24 months.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","10219"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418664","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-09-17","<p>The Government has committed £26.68 million to the Suffolk broadband project. The current contracted coverage is to provide superfast broadband access to 117,493 homes and businesses in the county, extending coverage to nearly 91% of premises. Procurement is still under way for part of the funding and coverage will be extended further once contracts are agreed. As 30 June 2015, the Suffolk project had covered 84,447 superfast premises.</p><p><br>Over £81 million of government funding has been committed to improving superfast broadband coverage in the East of England (including Buckinghamshire and Milton Keynes). This will support delivery of superfast broadband to 642,160 homes and businesses in the region that would otherwise not have gained coverage.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-09-17T14:40:07.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418664/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418664/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418664/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-09-14","Broadband: East of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps he is taking to increase broadband coverage and speed in Suffolk and the East of England.","false","Biography information for Jo Churchill","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill","10186"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418665","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-09-21","<p>The Office for National Statistics estimates that tourism directly contributed £59.6 billion to the UK economy in 2014, accounting for nearly 4% of the UK's Gross Domestic Product.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-09-21T13:59:51.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418665/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418665/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418665/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-09-14","Tourism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what proportion of the UK's gross domestic product is accounted for by tourism.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","10143"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418666","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-10-12","<p>The Government is working with the radio industry to improve digital radio coverage for listeners across the UK. DCMS, the BBC and commercial radio are jointly funding the long term expansion of the local DAB network with the building of 182 new digital transmitters across Scotland, Wales, England and Northern Ireland and technical/frequency changes at a further 49 existing local DAB sites by the end of September 2016. As a result of this new investment, according to the independent communications regulator Ofcom, it is expected that local DAB coverage in Scotland will increase from 65% to 86% of households.</p><p>Ofcom has published detailed maps outlining the improvements to local DAB coverage for the local digital radio multiplex areas in Scotland and these are available at:<a href="http://stakeholders.ofcom.org.uk/broadcasting/radio/coverage/dab-coverage-plans/" target="_blank">http://stakeholders.ofcom.org.uk/broadcasting/radio/coverage/dab-coverage-plans/</a></p><p>Separately the BBC is rolling out its national DAB network to a further 163 transmitter sites across the UK, scheduled for completion by the end of 2015. This programme will increase the coverage of its DAB network in Scotland from 91% to 95% of homes.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-10-12T12:38:03.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418666/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418666/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418666/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-09-14","Digital Broadcasting: Radio","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment his Department has made of the adequacy of DAB radio reception in Scotland; and what steps his Department has taken to improve poor reception in areas receiving low-quality coverage.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","10122"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418667","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-17","<p>The Ministry of Defence’s budget for the current financial year is £34.6bn. Spending on Counter Terrorism across government for this financial year totals more than £2bn spent by a range of departments, agencies and the police.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government announced at the Summer Budget that the MOD’s budget will rise by 0.5% per year in real terms from 2016/17 to 2020/21. There will also an additional £1.5bn per year by 2020/21 to spend on the military and intelligence agencies. The Government also committed to protect Counter Terrorism spending of more than £2bn in real terms.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Further details on funding allocations will be announced in the Spending Review on 25<sup>th</sup> November.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-09-17T12:47:19.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418667/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418667/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418667/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-14","Counter-terrorism and Defence","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what funding the Government has allocated to (a) defence and (b) counter-terrorism.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","10144"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418668","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-09-22","<p>The general principle of 'double medalling' remains extant. The issue of a medal for those who served on Arctic Convoys was looked at by Sir John Holmes in his Review of Military Medals, which was conducted independently of the Ministry of Defence. Sir John's recommendation was that an award (the Arctic Star) would be appropriate and this was agreed by the Committee on the Grant of Honours, Decorations and Medals and Her Majesty The Queen. Sir John felt that the Arctic Convoy operation was a separate and distinct campaign, geographically and in every other way, from what was happening in the Atlantic, and should have been considered in that light. As it would be impractical and unfair to withdraw the Atlantic Star from those awarded the Arctic Star, it is considered that double medalling has not occurred in this case.</p><p>While not diminishing the hardships and hazards of the Atlantic Convoys, the Arctic Convoys were subjected to uniquely appalling weather conditions and such an intensity of enemy air and sea attacks that they merited separate recognition from service in the Atlantic and it was therefore felt that this was an exceptional case.</p><p>With regards to double medalling and the Ushakov Medal, Her Majesty's Government have always been appreciative of the Russian Government's wish to honour these brave men. A recommendation was therefore made by the Foreign and Commonwealth Office to exceptionally allow the Ushakov Medal to be accepted and worn. President Putin presented the first medals during his visit to London on 16 June 2013.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2015-09-22T15:13:39.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418668/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418668/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418668/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-09-14","World War II: Military Decorations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 12 January 2015 to Question 219983, whether arrangements for the award of the Arctic Star medal indicate that the presumption against double-medalling set out in that Answer is no longer in force.","false","Biography information for Martin Vickers","Cleethorpes","Martin Vickers","10129"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418669","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-09-18","<p>NATO has published data on allies' defence spending which shows that the UK is estimated to spend 2.1% of its Gross Domestic Product on defence during financial year 2015-16. This data can be found in the document at the following link:</p><p>http://www.nato.int/nato_static_fl2014/assets/pdf/pdf_2015_06/20150622_PR_CP_2015_093-v2.pdf</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2015-09-18T13:25:00.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418669/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418669/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418669/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-09-14","Defence: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps his Department is taking to ensure it meets the NATO defence spending target for 2015.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","10203"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418670","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-09-17","<p>Russian military aviation has never entered British Sovereign Airspace without permission.</p><p>The RAF has identified, intercepted and escorted Russian military aircraft transiting through international airspace in the vicinity of the UK. Russian military flights can present a potential safety concern to other airspace users because of their practice of not communicating with air traffic control agencies with regard to their intentions, not filing a flight plan or not transmitting a recognisable secondary surveillance radar transponder code. Their activity therefore needs careful monitoring, which is why we intercept such flights.</p><p>The UK works closely with our Allies to keep NATO's airspace safe and secure and to enable a co-ordinated NATO air policing response.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2015-09-17T15:49:19.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418670/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418670/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418670/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-09-14","Russia: Military Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps he plans to take in response to incursions into British sovereign airspace by Russian Aerospace Forces.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","10197"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418671","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-09-22","<p>The processing of Freedom of Information requests is an integral part of civil servants' responsibilities. The number of hours spent on this activity is not separately identifiable.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2015-09-22T15:15:10.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418671/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418671/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418671/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-09-14","Ministry of Defence: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many hours his Department spent on processing freedom of information requests in each of the last 24 months.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","10220"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418672","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-09-17","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 10 September 2015 to Question 8831.</p><p>Our assessment has shown that there is no single reason behind the reduction in the overall number of visits by either the Army or the RAF in recent years.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2015-09-17T15:06:58.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418672/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418672/answer","20150910 - Q n A extract on Armed Forces Education.docx","20150910 - Q n A extract on Armed Forces Education.docx","Q n A extract on Armed Forces Education","Q n A extract on Armed Forces Education","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418672/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-09-14","Armed Forces: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 7 July 2015 to Question 4788, what assessment he has made of the reason why figures pertaining to the number of army and RAF visits to schools in the academic years from 2012 to 2015 are lower than figures for earlier years provided during the last Parliament by his Department; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","10215"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418673","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-09-22","<p>Although we welcome closer co-operation between the armed forces of EU and NATO member states, this needs to be based on improving defence capabilities across Europe, not creating new institutions. We will not support measures which would undermine member states' competence for their own military forces, or lead to competition and duplication with NATO.</p>","Canterbury","Mr Julian Brazier",,"2015-09-22T15:15:46.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418673/answer","Biography information for Sir Julian Brazier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418673/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418673/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-09-14","Armed Forces: EU Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment he has made of recent proposals by his German counterpart on increased integration and co-operation of EU member states' armed forces.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","10201"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418674","Department for Education","false","2015-09-22","<p>Freedom of Information (FOI) requests are dealt with by the relevant policy teams across the Department for Education as a core business function, with support from a small policy advisory team. The processing of FOI requests is accordingly an integral part of civil servants' responsibilities and the number of hours spent on this activity is not separately identifiable.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2015-09-22T08:54:43.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418674/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418674/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418674/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-09-14","Department for Education: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many hours her Department spent on processing freedom of information requests in each of the last 24 months.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","10221"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418675","Department for Education","false","2015-09-21","<p>The government has made it easier for all schools to make changes to the length, structure and content of the school day so that every school in England has the flexibility to decide when their school day should start and finish. We trust headteachers to decide how best to structure their school day to support their pupils’ education.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2015-09-21T13:33:17.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418675/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418675/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418675/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-09-14","Extracurricular Activities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will take steps to encourage the extension of the school day to create more opportunities for young people to access extracurricular activities.","false","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","10206"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418676","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-21","<p>Wave 14 of the Public Attitudes Tracker reveals that 75% of participants support the use of renewable energy to provide electricity, fuel and heat to the UK, 20% neither support nor oppose its use, and 4% oppose it.</p><p>The questions on individual renewable energy technologies were not included as part of the wave 14 survey, and will now feature bi-annually. This change is part of a wider review of the Public Attitudes Tracker, which commenced at the beginning of 2015, with the aim to ensure existing questions continue to add value and to increase capacity for additional topical questions going forward.</p><p>As three years’ worth of data reveals no clear pattern of change, DECC considered that understanding public attitudes to renewable technologies would not be hampered by reducing the frequency. Similar decisions were taken for the more frequent questions on energy saving and wasting, and energy security. The specific renewable questions will feature again in the next wave to be published on 10<sup>th</sup> November.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-09-21T12:28:07.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418676/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418676/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418676/answer","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418676/answer/previousversion/22117","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-14","Renewable Energy: Public Opinion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, if she will publish a disaggregation of the figure relating to the popularity of renewable energy amongst the public, with a breakdown of individual renewable energy technologies from her Department's Public Attitudes Tracker - Wave 14 document.","false","Biography information for Julie Elliott","Sunderland Central","Julie Elliott","10094"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418677","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-09-17","<p>Defra does not hold the information requested.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2015-09-17T16:15:12.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418677/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418677/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418677/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-09-14","Business: Carbon Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many (a) FTSE 100 and (b) FTSE 350 companies made voluntary climate disclosures beyond legal reporting requirements in the last year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Mr Alistair Carmichael","Orkney and Shetland","Mr Alistair Carmichael","10134"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418678","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-23","<p>The Government recognises the importance of the UK oil and gas industry to our economy and energy needs. Parliamentary business did not allow DECC Minsters to attend Offshore Europe but, as it is a key priority, the Oil and Gas Authority and DECC Officials played a leading role and we continue to maintain a dialogue with operators and other industry stakeholders. The Energy Minister’s first official visit was to Aberdeen to see first-hand what the industry is achieving even in these difficult times. She continues to visit and meet with many in the sector.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-09-23T12:20:11.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418678/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418678/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418678/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-14","Offshore Industry: Aberdeen","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what engagements (a) she and (b) Ministers in her Department attended at the Offshore Europe 2015 exhibition in Aberdeen in September 2015.","false","Biography information for Callum McCaig","Aberdeen South","Callum McCaig","10135"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418679","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-22","<p>DECC has been actively working with UKTI and other colleagues across Whitehall to identify new opportunities for the UK solar sector, promote the sector overseas through trade missions and other similar activities, and will continue to do so.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-09-22T12:29:59.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418679/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418679/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418679/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-14","Solar Power: Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what assessment her Department has made of the (a) export opportunities and (b) international growth potential of UK solar technology companies.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","10095"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418680","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-24","<p>The feed-in tariff review consultation invites comment and evidence in relation to a range of proposals for the future of the scheme, up to and including closure of the scheme. The impact assessment gives some indication of the basis on which those proposals have been formulated and the counterfactuals against which they have been developed.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-09-24T10:51:31.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418680/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418680/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418680/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-14","Renewable Energy: Feed-in Tariffs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what alternative options were considered by her Department when formulating proposals for the feed-in-tariff review.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","10096"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418681","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-23","<p>BIS’s report “The Size and Performance of the UK Low Carbon Economy” estimated that in 2013 there were over 34,000 jobs in the UK solar sector.</p><p>Our consultation on the feed-in tariff review reflects the need to balance sector support whilst keeping bills down for consumers.</p><p>We strongly welcome evidence from the sector during this review consultation, which ends on 23 October, and only then can we begin to analyse the impact on jobs.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-09-23T12:23:17.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418681/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418681/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418681/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-14","Solar Power: Feed-in Tariffs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what assessment her Department has made of the effect of proposed changes to the feed-in-tariff on employment in the solar industry.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","10097"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418682","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-24","<p>The number of hours spent on this activity in the Department of Energy and Climate Change is not separately identifiable.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-09-24T10:37:11.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418682/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418682/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418682/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-14","Department for Energy and Climate Change: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how many hours her Department spent on processing freedom of information requests in each of the last 24 months.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","10222"
