"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418684","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-09-17","<p>The Government has committed to undertaking a review in 2016/17 of intra-UK CAP budget allocations.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-09-17T11:17:10.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418684/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418684/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418684/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-09-14","Common Agricultural Policy: Subsidies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will make it her policy to conduct her Department's planned review of the convergence uplift payments immediately.","false","Biography information for Ian Blackford","Ross, Skye and Lochaber","Ian Blackford","10190"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418685","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-18","<p>The Government is focused on delivering a successful renegotiation: it believes it can and will succeed in reforming and renegotiating our relationship with the EU and campaigning to keep the UK in the EU on that basis. The Prime Minister, my right hon. Friend the Member for Witney (Mr Cameron) is confident of achieving this but has said that if we do not achieve the necessary reforms, he rules nothing out.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2015-09-18T12:28:21.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418685/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418685/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418685/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-14","UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what planning the Government has undertaken on the steps necessary for the UK to withdraw from the EU in the event that the outcome of the EU referendum is a vote to leave.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","10133"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418686","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-21","The Forced Marriage Unit provides a range of support and assistance to both women and men who are at risk of forced marriage. In 2014 the Forced Marriage Unit gave advice or support, related to a possible forced marriage, in 1267 cases. To provide more information on the nature of the assistance provided, including repatriation, would involve a disproportionate cost.","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps",,"2015-09-21T13:30:11.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418686/answer","Biography information for Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418686/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418686/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-14","Forced Marriage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many women have been repatriated after seeking help from the risk of forced marriage from the Forced Marriage Unit or a British Post overseas in the last 12 months for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Fiona Mactaggart","Slough","Fiona Mactaggart","10115"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418687","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-23","As I said to Parliament on 15 September, the Sri Lankan parliamentary elections in August were the freest, fairest and least violent in living memory. The Prime Minister, my right hon. Friend the Member for Witney (Mr Cameron) and The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond) congratulated the Government of Sri Lanka on the peaceful elections and reiterated that the United Kingdom remains a steadfast partner on reconciliation and peace. The August elections in Sri Lanka have resulted in a government committed to reconciliation and peace building. President Sirisena set out his government’s priorities to Parliament on 1 September. These included constitutional reforms; abolishing the Executive Presidency; electoral reform; strengthening institutions; and reforming the public sector and welfare systems. While we recognise that more needs to be done there has been some early progress with constitutional reforms strengthening democratic checks and balances, some land previously under military use being returned and military Governors in the north and east being replaced by civilians. Within this context, on 16 September I welcomed the publication of the Office of the High Commissioner of Human Rights report into allegations of serious violations and abuses of human rights in Sri Lanka.","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2015-09-23T09:38:30.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418687/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418687/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418687/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-14","Sri Lanka: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the political and security situation in Sri Lanka; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","Wycombe","Steve Baker","10193"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418688","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-22","<p>Officials from our Embassy in Tel Aviv have discussed the situation in Syria with the Israeli authorities on several occasions. Our Ambassador to Israel raised the issue with the Israeli Defence Minister on 27 August and more recently with officials from the Israeli National Security Council on 9 September. The Prime Minister, my right hon. Friend the Member for Witney (David Cameron), and the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Philip Hammond) discussed security in the region with Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu on 10 September.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-09-22T12:00:18.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418688/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418688/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418688/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-14","Syria: Islamic State","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his Israeli counterpart on tackling Islamic State militants in Syria.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","10195"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418689","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-22","<p>The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend the member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Philip Hammond) has discussed the issue of the migration of Syrian refugees with Secretary of State Kerry, and will be doing so again later this week.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-09-22T12:28:45.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418689/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418689/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418689/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-14","Syria: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his US counterpart on the migration of refugees from Syria.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","10196"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418690","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-21","We closely monitor the political and security situation in Israel and the Occupied Palestinian Territories. The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond) discussed the future of the peace process, the situation on the ground and developments in the region with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu on 10 September. Most recently, we have been concerned by violence at the Temple Mount / Haram Al Sharif compound. I issued a statement on this matter on 16 September.","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-09-21T13:42:15.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418690/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418690/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418690/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-14","Israel: Palestinians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the political and security situation in Israel and Palestine; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","Wycombe","Steve Baker","10179"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418691","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-17","<p>We follow developments in Kashmir closely. Officials from our High Commissions in Delhi and Islamabad regularly discuss the situation in Kashmir with the governments of both India and Pakistan, and travel to the region periodically to see the situation on the ground for themselves.</p><p>The long standing position of the UK is that it is for India and Pakistan to find a lasting resolution to the situation in Kashmir, taking into account the wishes of the Kashmiri people. It is not for the UK to prescribe a solution or to act as a mediator. We encourage both sides to maintain positive dialogue, but the pace and scope of this is for them to determine.</p><p> </p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2015-09-17T12:42:11.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418691/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418691/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418691/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-14","Kashmir: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the political and security situation in Kashmir; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","Wycombe","Steve Baker","10180"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418692","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-18","<p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) does not hold data on the number of hours spent processing Freedom of Information requests.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2015-09-18T12:31:39.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418692/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418692/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418692/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-14","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many hours his Department spent on processing freedom of information requests in each of the last 24 months.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","10224"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418693","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-09-17","<p>Our Intimidation Policy supports all local staff, regardless of role or employment duration, who may be facing security risks as a result of their work with British Forces. The UK is the only nation with a permanent team in country to address the concerns of those worried about their safety, including trained police officers to investigate reported intimidation incidents. These experts thoroughly and professionally investigate all claims of intimidation and have provided support to some 300 former local staff. This support has included bespoke security advice and financial support for some 30 relocations within Afghanistan.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2015-09-17T15:48:05.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418693/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418693/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418693/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-09-14","Afghanistan: Interpreters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what support his Department is providing to vulnerable interpreters in Afghanistan who have worked with British armed forces.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","10200"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418694","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-17","<p>The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend the Member for Runnymead and Weybridge (Mr Hammond) has not had any discussions with his New Zealand counterpart on this matter. The decision to hold a referendum is a matter for the New Zealand people.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2015-09-17T13:31:32.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418694/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418694/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418694/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-14","New Zealand: Flags","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his New Zealand counterpart on the upcoming referendum on that country's national flag.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","10199"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418695","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-18","<p>The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend the member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond) and I have raised property issues experienced by British nationals with the Cypriot Foreign Minister, Ioannis Kasoulides. The Foreign Secretary raised property issues with Mr Kasoulides whilst in Cyprus on 17 July 2015 and I raised the subject with Mr Kasoulides in London on 12 March. We will continue to raise property issues at appropriate times both at official and Ministerial level.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2015-09-18T12:37:11.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418695/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418695/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418695/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-14","Cyprus: Property","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what further discussions he plans to have with his Cypriot counterpart on the misselling of mortgages by Alpha Panareti; and when those discussions will take place.","false","Biography information for Gareth Johnson","Dartford","Gareth Johnson","10149"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418696","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-21","<p>We are deeply concerned about the treatment of the LGBT community in the Occupied Palestinian Territories (OPTs), particularly in Gaza where they are subject to widespread social discrimination for cultural and religious reasons. Homosexuality remains a taboo subject in the OPTs. In some places, such as Ramallah, these taboos are relaxed, but in more conservative areas the situation is very challenging. There are no laws protecting LGBT people, however we are not aware of any recent legal cases being prosecuted against LGBT people.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-09-21T14:50:51.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418696/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418696/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418696/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-14","Palestinians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the treatment of gay, lesbian and transgender people by the Palestinian Police and Palestinian Authority.","false","Biography information for Andrew Percy","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy","10146"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418697","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-22","<p>The government believes that the root causes of migration must be addressed, and not just the symptoms. A comprehensive solution is needed that will reduce the pull and push factors causing people to leave their countries of origin. We must also address the transit routes being used, as well as disrupting the criminal elements who are smuggling and trafficking humans. We are working closely with EU and international partners to find such a solution.</p><p>Because it is the gateway to western Mediterranean irregular migration, the government is also working with other countries to bring about a functioning government in Libya.</p><p>The government has provided substantial development and humanitarian assistance to help refugees from the civil war in Syria. The Unted Kingdom has now committed more than £1 billion of aid to help people displaced by the conflict there, both within Syria and in neighbouring countries, and to encourage stability. This makes the UK the EU’s largest donor, and second largest donor (after the USA) overall.</p><p>United Kingdom support has helped to provide more than 20 million food rations, 2.5 million medical consultations, and given 1.6 million people access to clean water . The UK is providing education to a quarter of a million children in the area.</p><p>Additionally, the Prime Minister announced on 7 September that the UK will resettle 20,000 Syrian refugees from the region over the course of this parliament.</p><p>An EU/Africa Summit in Valletta in November offers the opportunity to develop a robust and comprehensive set of proposals to deal with the upstream cause of irregular migration. We are fully engaged in the preparations.</p><p>The Prime Minister, my right hon. Friend the Member for Witney (Mr Cameron), The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond), The Secretary of State for International Development, my right hon. Friend the member for Putney (Ms Greening) and I have all discussed preparations for Valetta with other European governments and the European Commission.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2015-09-22T15:27:53.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418697/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418697/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418697/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-14","Mediterranean Sea: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to address the root causes of the migrant situation in the Mediterranean.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","10164"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418698","Department of Health","false","2015-09-21","<p>Correspondence records indicate that Ministers of the Department have received no letters from universities or research institutions specifically about future allocations to the Department’s budget for research and development following the 2015 Spending Review.</p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-09-21T14:50:02.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418698/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418698/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418698/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-14","Research: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 11 September 2015 to Question 8266, what representations he has received from (a) universities and (b) other research institutions on the future funding of research budgets; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","10152"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418699","Department of Health","false","2015-09-17","<p>National Health Service staff earning above £21,000 had their pay frozen during 2011/12 and 2012/13 with, since then, most staff receiving at least 1% increases. This approach to pay has helped protect jobs in the NHS and maintain services for patients.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>There is no evidence that the pay freeze affected staff morale. While the NHS Staff Survey, which provides the most comprehensive assessment of staff views about working in the NHS, does not directly measure staff morale, staff engagement, which includes staff motivation at work, staff recommending their trust as a place to work or receive treatment, and the percentage of staff able to contribute towards improvements at work, has remained high with a score of 3.76/5 in 2014 (latest available) rising from 3.68/5 in 2012 (the first year staff engagement was included).</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-09-17T15:58:15.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418699/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418699/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418699/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-14","NHS: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the effect of the public sector pay freeze on NHS staff morale; and whether he plans to survey NHS staff on that matter.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","10139"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418700","Department of Health","false","2015-09-17","<p>NHS England contracts for orthodontic services at a local level taking account of the local oral health needs. Therefore opening hours are a matter for agreement between local commissioners and providers.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-09-17T10:09:04.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418700/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418700/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418700/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-14","Dental Services: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will take steps to encourage orthodontists to offer NHS appointments to children outside school hours.","false","Biography information for Dr Tania Mathias","Twickenham","Dr Tania Mathias","10177"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418701","Department of Health","false","2015-09-17","<p>The UK National Screening Committee (UK NSC) which advises Ministers and the National Health Service in all four countries about all aspects of screening is currently looking at the evidence for a variety of tests (including doppler scans) and treatments to see if they would be able to help to reduce stillbirths. The UK NSC will evaluate the benefits and risks of each test and treatment against its internationally recognised criteria before making a recommendation on their introduction.</p><p> </p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2015-09-17T14:50:42.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418701/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418701/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418701/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-14","Pregnancy: Screening","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment the NHS has made of the potential benefits and disadvantages of the use of Doppler scans in preventing stillbirths.","false","Biography information for Dr Tania Mathias","Twickenham","Dr Tania Mathias","10175"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418702","Department of Health","false","2015-09-17","<p>The table below shows the number of full time equivalent health visitors employed in England at the mid-point in each year from 2011 to 2014, and the latest available figure in 2015. Data from 2012 onwards is taken from the Health Visitor Minimum Data Set (HV-MDS) which commenced in April 2012 and also includes data for health visitors employed by organisations that do not use Electronic Staff record (ESR) but do provide NHS-funded services, such as local authorities.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Full time equivalent figures are used as this is the most accurate measure of service capacity.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>30 September 2011 <sup>1</sup></p></td><td><p>30 September 2012 <sup>2</sup></p></td><td><p>30 September 2013</p></td><td><p>30 September 2014</p></td><td><p>31 May 2015</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>7,941</p></td><td><p>8,678</p></td><td><p>9,550</p></td><td><p>10,800</p></td><td><p>11,850</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><em> </em></p><p> </p><p><em>Source:</em> Health and Social Care Information Centre NHS Hospital and Community health service monthly workforce statistics</p><p> </p><p><em> </em></p><p> </p><p><em>Notes:</em></p><p> </p><p>1. The data for 2011 covers only those health visitors on the ESR.</p><p> </p><p>2. The figure for September 2012 is different from the published figure due to a known over count (of 14).</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-09-17T15:56:12.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418702/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418702/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418702/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-14","Health Visitors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many health visitors were employed in (a) 2011-12, (b) 2012-13, (c) 2013-14 and (d) 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","10170"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418703","Department of Health","false","2015-09-22","<p>Staff throughout the Department consider requests made under the Freedom of Information Act as part of their duties, and time spent is not accounted for separately. A central team of five full-time staff manages the caseload and gives advice on Freedom of Information Act requests.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-09-22T09:51:10.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418703/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418703/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418703/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-14","Department of Health: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many hours his Department spent on processing freedom of information requests in each of the last 24 months.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","10225"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418704","Department of Health","false","2015-09-17","<p>Diagnosed diabetes prevalence is taken from the Quality and Outcomes Framework (QOF) and represents all patients who have been diagnosed with diabetes and included on GP registers.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Diabetes prevalence is increasing. Diagnosed diabetes prevalence has increased from 2.3 million (5.3%) in 2009/10 to 2.8 million (6.2%) in 2013/14; an increase of nearly half a million people.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Public Health England’s diabetes prevalence model estimates total diabetes prevalence for England and for all local authorities and clinical commissioning groups (CCG) in England. The model reflects the prevalence of diabetes (diagnosed and undiagnosed) and adjusts for the age, sex, ethnic group and deprivation pattern of the local population.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The estimated total diabetes prevalence using the diabetes prevalence model is 7.5% in 2014.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>If current trends continue then we estimate that by 2030 there will be over 4 million people with diabetes. This represents 8.8% of the population aged 16 years and over.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>This data is publically available on the Healthier Lives website at:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="http://healthierlives.phe.org.uk/topic/diabetes" target="_blank">http://healthierlives.phe.org.uk/topic/diabetes</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The website also provides diagnosed prevalence at the CCG level.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Tackling diabetes is of great concern to this Government. Building on the National Diabetes Prevention Programme, the Department is developing its plans to improve outcomes for those at risk of and with diabetes. These will be announced in due course.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","10120","2015-09-17T15:53:58.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418704/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418704/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418704/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-14","Diabetes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent assessment his Department has made of the prevalence of diabetes; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","10181"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418705","Department of Health","false","2015-09-17","<p>The information is not available in the format requested.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-09-17T16:08:39.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418705/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418705/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418705/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-14","Mental Health Services: East of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many people from within Norfolk and Suffolk Foundation Trust region have been required to travel outside their trust areas to receive emergency mental health treatment in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jo Churchill","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill","10130"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418706","Department of Health","false","2015-09-22","<p>The information on the cost to the public purse of employing agency staff to cover staff shortages within the National Health Service in the last three years is not held centrally.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-09-22T10:03:30.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418706/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418706/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418706/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-14","NHS: Temporary Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the cost to the public purse of employing agency staff to cover staff shortages within the NHS in the last three years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","10136"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418707","Department of Health","false","2015-09-21","<p>Data in respect of the number of unfilled vacancies in the National Health Service is not collected by the Department.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2015-09-21T15:54:09.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418707/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418707/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418707/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-14","NHS Trusts: Vacancies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the number of unfilled vacancies in NHS trusts.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","10141"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418708","Department of Health","false","2015-09-21","<p>A person who is not ordinarily resident in the United Kingdom is subject to the National Health Service (Charges to Overseas Visitors) Regulations 2015 which apply charges to overseas visitors for any NHS hospital services they receive, unless an exemption category in the Charging Regulations applies.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Overseas visitors who ordinarily reside outside the European Economic Area (EEA) and who have not paid the Health Surcharge, nor meet any exemption from charge will be charged 150% of the national tariff. Charging 150% of the national tariff provides for additional administrations charges incurred with treating overseas visitors such as translation services.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Charges for overseas visitors who ordinarily reside within EEA states can be claimed from the country they normally reside in.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-09-21T15:44:40.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418708/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418708/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418708/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-14","NHS: Translation Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether NHS England seeks to recover the cost of its translation and interpretation services for patients who are not UK residents.","false","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan","10102"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418709","Department of Health","false","2015-09-21","<p>We do not hold this information centrally. National Health Service organisations have a duty to follow equalities legislation. This includes making sure their communities can understand information about the NHS services and that patients and clinicians can communicate with each other. We encourage the NHS to be efficient and save money by working together and sharing resources.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","10104","2015-09-21T15:52:13.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418709/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418709/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418709/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-14","Hospitals: Translation Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much NHS England spent on translation and interpretation services for hospital patients in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan","10103"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418710","Department of Health","false","2015-09-21","<p>We do not hold this information centrally. National Health Service organisations have a duty to follow equalities legislation. This includes making sure their communities can understand information about the NHS services and that patients and clinicians can communicate with each other. We encourage the NHS to be efficient and save money by working together and sharing resources.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","10103","2015-09-21T15:52:13.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418710/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418710/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418710/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-14","NHS: Translation Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what information NHS England holds on expenditure on translation and interpretation services for (a) EU and (b) non-EU patients.","false","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan","10104"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418711","Department of Health","false","2015-09-21","<p>NHS Blood and Transplant (NHSBT) is the organ donation organisation for the United Kingdom and is funded by the Department and the Devolved Administrations. Its remit also includes the provision of a reliable efficient supply of blood in England and North Wales, and providing tissues to the National Health Service.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>NHSBT actively campaigns to promote public awareness about the importance of organ and tissue donation and transplantation and to encourage people to join the NHS Organ Donor Register (ODR). Underpinning NHSBT’s work to promote organ donation is encouraging people to join the ODR and then to let their loved ones know that they have made a decision to donate. Encouraging this conversation is important as families are more likely to agree to donation if they know that is what their loved one wanted.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Department has also worked to raise general awareness of persistent inequalities people from a Black, Asian and Minority Ethnic (BAME) background face when trying to find a suitable bone marrow or organ donor and supports the work of the National BAME Transplant Alliance. Launched in 2012, this group helps to coordinate the work of BAME organisations promoting donation.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The UK’s health administrations, many charities, community groups and hospitals also work hard to promote organ and tissue donation and NHSBT work collaboratively with them wherever possible.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>NHSBT regularly campaigns to encourage more of the eligible population, including from the BAME community to donate blood. Although blood stocks are currently in a healthy position, there is always a need for new donors to fill the gaps left by existing donors who are no longer able to give blood - to ensure that we have the right mix of blood groups to match patients’ needs. NHSBT co-ordinates local and national awareness campaigns, such as the current ‘Bleed for England’ campaign, which are intended to motivate thousands of people to start donating blood.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In addition, the Department funds the national Gamete Donation Trust through a contract to provide a range of services to promote gamate donation and support the recruitment and retention of egg and sperm donors, which helps infertile couples.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-09-21T14:39:02.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418711/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418711/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418711/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-14","Donors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to promote the donation of blood, organs and other organic materials.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","10111"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418712","Department of Health","false","2015-09-17","<p>Diagnosed diabetes prevalence is taken from the Quality and Outcomes Framework (QOF) and represents all patients who have been diagnosed with diabetes and included on GP registers.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Diabetes prevalence is increasing. Diagnosed diabetes prevalence has increased from 2.3 million (5.3%) in 2009/10 to 2.8 million (6.2%) in 2013/14; an increase of nearly half a million people.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Public Health England’s diabetes prevalence model estimates total diabetes prevalence for England and for all local authorities and clinical commissioning groups (CCG) in England. The model reflects the prevalence of diabetes (diagnosed and undiagnosed) and adjusts for the age, sex, ethnic group and deprivation pattern of the local population.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The estimated total diabetes prevalence using the diabetes prevalence model is 7.5% in 2014.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>If current trends continue then we estimate that by 2030 there will be over 4 million people with diabetes. This represents 8.8% of the population aged 16 years and over.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>This data is publically available on the Healthier Lives website at:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="http://healthierlives.phe.org.uk/topic/diabetes" target="_blank">http://healthierlives.phe.org.uk/topic/diabetes</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The website also provides diagnosed prevalence at the CCG level.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Tackling diabetes is of great concern to this Government. Building on the National Diabetes Prevention Programme, the Department is developing its plans to improve outcomes for those at risk of and with diabetes. These will be announced in due course.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","10181","2015-09-17T15:53:59.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418712/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","ht