"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418713","Department of Health","false","2015-09-17","<p>Information on the country of birth of National Health Service staff is not collected centrally.</p><p> </p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2015-09-17T15:26:43.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418713/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418713/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418713/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-14","Nurses: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate his Department has made of the number of nurses not born in the EU employed by the NHS in England in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","10121"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418714","Home Office","false","2015-09-17","<p>It is not Her Majesty’s Passport Office (HM Passport Office) normal practice to discuss individual cases in a PQ. However, HM Passport Office confirms that they will be contacting the Honourable Member by 18 September to advise him of the progress of this application. HM Passport Office can also confirm that they are attempting to contact the constituent to update him.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-09-17T11:26:38.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418714/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418714/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418714/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-14","HM Passport Office: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when the Passport Office plans to inform the hon. Member's constituent of the outcome of their passport application, reference 681 355 476.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","10119"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418715","Home Office","false","2015-09-18","<p>Following the decision to suspend temporarily the Detained Fast Track (DFT), we are reviewing the system and the safeguarding mechanisms. As in the statement made to the House on 2 July, this work will be informed by the findings of the Stephen Shaw review which is due to report shortly. We will update Parliament on revised arrangements for recommencing DFT once they have been finalised.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-09-18T15:34:24.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418715/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418715/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418715/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-14","Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Written Statement of 2 July 2015 HCWS83, what recent assessment she has made of the adequacy of safeguards within the Detained Fast Track procedure to protect vulnerable applicants.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","10105"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418716","Home Office","false","2015-09-18","<p>Information on the number of people with a mental health disorder detained in the immigration detention estate is not recorded centrally. Providing this information from an examination of individual records would be at disproportionate cost.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-09-18T15:46:23.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418716/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418716/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418716/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-14","Immigrants: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of the number of people with a mental health disorder who were detained in immigration detention in the 12 months to June 2015.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","10142"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418717","Home Office","false","2015-09-18","<p>The UK is a world-leader in the fight to stamp out this brutal practice, with our Forced Marriage Unit (FMU) leading efforts to combat forced marriage both at home and abroad. In 2014, the FMU gave advice or support related to a possible forced marriage in 1,267 cases. To provide a breakdown on the nature of the assistance provided, including referrals to the police, would incur a disproportionate cost.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-09-18T10:41:51.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418717/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418717/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418717/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-14","Forced Marriage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many cases of suspected forced marriage have been reported by the forced marriage unit to the police for investigation and possible prosecution in the last 12 months for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Fiona Mactaggart","Slough","Fiona Mactaggart","10114"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418718","Home Office","false","2015-09-28","<p>Individuals who have been identified as victims of trafficking by the competent authorities are normally considered suitable for detention in only very exceptional circumstances, which include cases where there is a risk of public harm. This data is not collected centrally and accurate figures are not available.</p><p>Once a person is detained their continued detention remains under review by the Home Office at least at monthly intervals, and earlier in response to any change of circumstances that might have a material effect on their detention.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2015-09-28T11:17:47.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418718/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418718/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418718/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-14","Immigrants: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent estimate she has made of the number of victims of trafficking who were detained in immigration detention since (a) January 2015 and (b) June 2015.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","10189"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418719","Home Office","false","2015-10-08","<p>The number of hours spent on this activity in the Home Office is not separately identifiable.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-10-08T11:46:25.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418719/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418719/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418719/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-14","Home Office: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many hours her Department spent on processing freedom of information requests in each of the last 24 months.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","10226"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418720","Home Office","false","2015-09-18","<p>Following significant abuse in the English Language sector that was uncovered in 2014, a procurement exercise was undertaken to strengthen the arrangements for English language testing for immigration purposes. As part of the procurement, any test provider could have made a bid to be included on the list of Secure English language tests.</p><p>In order to ensure that all English tests are administered to the same security standards, the procurement exercise included tests suitable for settlement and naturalisation purposes, the decision was taken to apply the SELT arrangements to settlement and naturalisation applications from November 2015.</p><p>Trinity and the IELTS Consortium were the only test providers to meet these requirements.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-09-18T15:34:50.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418720/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418720/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418720/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-14","English Language: Qualifications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, for what reasons her Department decided to remove the Scottish Qualifications Authority's English for speakers of other languages examinations from her Department's list of recognised qualifications.","false","Biography information for Mr Alistair Carmichael","Orkney and Shetland","Mr Alistair Carmichael","10205"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418721","Home Office","false","2015-09-18","<p>Details of the group, its purpose, and membership have already been published on GOV.UK. The Home Secretary updated the House on 16 September on the work of the group.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-09-18T16:05:21.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418721/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418721/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418721/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-14","Ministerial Committee for Syrian Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will publish the minutes of the first meeting of the Ministerial Committee for Syrian refugees held on 11 September 2015; and how often that committee plans to meet.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","10171"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418722","Home Office","false","2015-09-18","<p>It is not possible at the moment to say how many vulnerable individuals and families will be resettled in specific areas across the UK. Our existing policy, based on the Immigration and Asylum Act 1999 drawn up by the last Labour Government, is aimed at ensuring that asylum seekers and refugees are dispersed across the country so that no individual local authority bears a disproportionate share of the burden. We are working closely with a wide range of partners, including local authorities and civil society organisations, to ensure that this remains the case.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-09-18T15:50:29.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418722/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418722/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418722/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-14","Refugees: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of the proportion of the 20,000 Syrian refugees that will be admitted to the UK that will be settled in the local authority areas of (a) West Oxfordshire, (b) Cheshire East and (c) the Royal Borough of Windsor and Maidenhead.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","10172"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418723","Home Office","false","2015-09-17","<p>Serco is one of three providers who operate under the COMPASS contracts to provide accommodation for destitute asylum seekers. There is currently no intention of providing accommodation for the expanded resettlement scheme through the COMPASS contracts.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-09-17T11:24:37.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418723/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418723/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418723/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-14","Refugees: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether the 20,000 Syrian refugees to be taken in by the UK will be housed by Serco.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","10173"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418724","Home Office","false","2015-09-17","<p>We cannot divulge the payments made under the COMPASS contracts for reasons of commercial sensitivity.</p><p>However, the costs of the COMPASS contracts were anticipated at the time of procurement to be £172 million in the North West of England, and £82 million in Scotland and Northern Ireland. These costs relate to the full seven year life of the contracts.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-09-17T11:25:00.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418724/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418724/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418724/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-14","Compass Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of the overall cost to the public purse of Serco's contract with the Government to re-house asylum seekers.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","10174"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418725","Home Office","false","2015-10-05","<p>The Government will publish its Counter-Extremism strategy in the near future. There are no plans for a national register of faith leaders.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","10155","2015-10-05T13:32:57.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418725/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418725/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418725/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-14","Ministers of Religion: Registration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the effectiveness of her Department's plans for a proposed national register of faith leaders in countering extremism.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","10154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418726","Home Office","false","2015-10-05","<p>The Government will publish its Counter-Extremism strategy in the near future. There are no plans for a national register of faith leaders.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","10154","2015-10-05T13:32:57.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418726/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418726/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418726/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-14","Ministers of Religion: Registration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what plans her Department has under its proposal for a national register of faith leaders to (a) vet faith leaders from outside the UK before or after their arrival in the UK, (b) subject faith leaders already in the UK to the same level of vetting as applies to those entering the UK, (c) exclude teachers or priests from any particular religion or denomination from the requirement to register and (d) deal with faith leaders entering the UK or already resident here who are believed to be a threat to national security.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","10155"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418727","Home Office","false","2015-09-18","<p>I replied to the Honourable Lady's letters on 18 September 2015.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-09-18T16:04:24.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418727/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418727/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418727/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-14","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when she plans to reply to the letters from the hon. Member for Wigan of 13 July 2015 and 2 September 2015 on Serco and asylum seekers in the North West.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","10137"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418728","Home Office","false","2015-09-18","<p>From 2010 up to 30 June this year, 3,822 refugees have been accommodated by 14 local authorities under the Gateway Protection Programme. All 14 local authorities are in England. A further 22 refugees have been resettled with their relatives and were not accommodated by any local authority.</p><p>It would not be appropriate for us to release details of where individuals are currently being placed or where they may be placed in the future, as this may undermine their privacy.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-09-18T15:35:10.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418728/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418728/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418728/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-14","Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many refugees have been accommodated in each local authority in (a) England, (b) Wales and (c) Scotland under the Gateway scheme in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","10166"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418729","Home Office","false","2015-09-16","<p>The Metropolitan Police Service first had authorisation to use a collapsible baton on 28 June 1995.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-09-16T17:00:41.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418729/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418729/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418729/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-14","Metropolitan Police: Equipment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when the Metropolitan Police first had authorisation to issue and allow officers to use a collapsible baton.","false","Biography information for Sir Peter Bottomley","Worthing West","Sir Peter Bottomley","10208"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418730","Home Office","false","2015-09-18","<p>The Home Office does not hold information on when police officers are authorised to drive police vehicles. This information is held by individual police forces.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-09-18T09:57:49.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418730/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418730/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418730/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-14","Gurpal Virdi","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what information her Department holds on when former Metropolitan Police officer Gurpal Virdi was authorised to drive a police vehicle.","false","Biography information for Sir Peter Bottomley","Worthing West","Sir Peter Bottomley","10209"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418731","Department for International Development","false","2015-09-17","<p>The UK government has been at the forefront of the refugee crisis and is taking every opportunity to work with partners across Europe and in the wider international community to ensure that, collectively, we are able to provide a significant and comprehensive development response.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The UK is contributing over £1 billion in response to the humanitarian crisis in Syria and the region and is urging the international community as a whole to step up life-saving assistance and protection for refugees and vulnerable people.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The UK lobbied hard to mobilise funding from other donors ahead of the third Kuwait Pledging Conference on 31 March, which raised $3.6 billion. The UK has also co-sponsored UN Security Council Resolutions 2165 and 2191 which has enabled the UN to deliver aid across border without the consent of the Syrian regime in order to assist those in the hardest to reach areas.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2015-09-17T15:55:28.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418731/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418731/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418731/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-09-14","Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps she is taking to help co-ordinate (a) a European and (b) an international response to the refugee situation.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","10213"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418732","Department for International Development","false","2015-09-21","<p>As with all UK Official Development Assistance (ODA), the UK complies with the OECD DAC’s guidelines, including for costs relating to support to refugees in donor countries.</p><p> </p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2015-09-21T12:11:10.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418732/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418732/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418732/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-09-14","Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what time limits there are on funding allocated by her Department to local authorities to support incoming refugees.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","10165"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418733","Department for International Development","false","2015-09-17","<p>Additional funds to support refugees in 2015/16 will be provided without directly impacting existing spending plans. Departmental budgets for 2016/17 onwards will be announced as part of the 2015 Spending Review.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2015-09-17T16:01:17.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418733/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418733/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418733/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-09-14","Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, from projects in which Commonwealth countries she plans to reallocate funds from the foreign aid budget to settle refugees within the UK.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","10198"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418734","Department for International Development","false","2015-09-17","<p>DFID has not funded any projects specifically supporting communications infrastructure in the British Overseas Territories in the last two years. Support for communications infrastructure is provided as part of annual budget aid settlements to Montserrat, St Helena and Pitcairn.</p><p> </p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2015-09-17T16:43:08.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418734/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418734/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418734/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-09-14","British Overseas Territories: Communication","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how much her Department has spent on communications infrastructure in British Overseas Territories in each of the last two years.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","10202"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418735","Department for International Development","false","2015-09-21","<p>All DFID staff are responsible for ensuring that the Department is able to meet its legislative obligations under the Freedom of Information Act 2000 and may be involved in the processing of requests. The number of hours spent on this activity is not separately identifiable.</p><p> </p>","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps",,"2015-09-21T12:27:51.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418735/answer","Biography information for Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418735/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418735/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-09-14","Department for International Development: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how many hours her Department spent on processing freedom of information requests in each of the last 24 months.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","10227"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418736","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-09-18","<p /> <p>Following completion of our consultation on the courts estate, consideration will be given as to the best way to dispose of the court to maximise value for money for the tax payer. Capital receipts from the sale of any surplus assets would be reinvested into HM Courts &amp; Tribunals Service to help create a more modern, efficient and user-focused courts system.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2015-09-18T10:49:24.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418736/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418736/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418736/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-09-14","Courts: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what plans the Government has for the use of court buildings which may be closed under current proposals; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Christina Rees","Neath","Christina Rees","10107"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418737","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-09-21","<p>There is no evidence that magistrates are resigning in greater numbers this year than in previous years.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2015-09-21T14:15:09.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418737/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418737/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418737/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-09-14","Magistrates: Resignations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps he plans to take to ensure continued effective delivery of local justice after the resignation of large numbers of long-serving magistrates.","false","Biography information for Christina Rees","Neath","Christina Rees","10108"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418738","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-09-21","<p /> <p>The Department does not hold this information which could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2015-09-21T14:53:14.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418738/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418738/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418738/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-09-14","Ministry of Justice: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many hours his Department spent on processing freedom of information requests in each of the last 24 months.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","10228"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418739","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-09-18","<p>The information requested is not centrally recorded and could be obtained only at disproportionate cost.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2015-09-18T10:57:48.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418739/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418739/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418739/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-09-14","Prisons: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many prisoners are undergoing work placements and schemes within prison whilst awaiting deportation.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","10158"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418740","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-09-28","<p /> <p>The majority of prisoner clothing is manufactured within prison workshops. This provides meaningful work for prisoners and helps keep costs down.</p><p> </p><p>From April 2014 to March 2015, £630,750 was spent on clothing from outside suppliers to top up production from prison workshops.</p><p> </p><p>Individual prisons can choose to recover the costs of clothing for prisoners at the discretion of the governor. Data on this is not held centrally.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2015-09-28T15:46:14.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418740/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418740/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418740/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-09-14","Prisoners: Clothing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much has been spent on purchasing clothing for prisoners in the latest period for which figures are available; and how much of that cost will be recovered from prisoners.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","10157"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418741","Attorney General","false","2015-09-30","<p>The decision to prosecute Gurpal Virdi for misconduct in public office and indecent assault was made in accordance with the Full Code Test as set out in the Code for Crown Prosecutors. The case was handled by a specialist unit within the Crown Prosecution Service (CPS), prosecuted by Treasury Counsel and supervised at very senior levels of the CPS.</p><p>There was detailed legal argument and a defence application to dismiss the case before trial. The application failed. At trial no defence submission was made to the trial judge that the matter should not be left to the jury. Mr Virdi was subsequently acquitted by the jury after a full trial.</p><p>I understand that the CPS has already written to my Hon. Friend with a more detailed explanation of the decision making in this case and I am satisfied that the CPS have handled the prosecution appropriately. However, I am happy to meet my Hon. Friend along with representatives of the CPS to discuss the case further if required.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2015-09-30T10:16:16.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418741/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418741/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418741/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2015-09-14","Gurpal Virdi","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, if he will meet hon. Members and representatives of the Crown Prosecution Service to discuss the prosecution of Councillor Gurpai Virdi in the case heard at Southwark Crown Court starting on 27 July 2015.","false","Biography information for Sir Peter Bottomley","Worthing West","Sir Peter Bottomley","10211"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418742","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-09-18","<p /> <p>Section 1 of the Sexual Offences (Amendment) Act 1992 provides for lifetime anonymity for complainants in a wide range of sexual offences without the necessity of a court order. That provision applies in the case involving the recent prosecution of Councillor Gurpal Virdi.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2015-09-18T10:24:12.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418742/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418742/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418742/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-09-14","Gurpal Virdi","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether the complainant and first witness in the recent prosecution of Councillor Gurpai Virdi is subject to a court order of anonymity.","false","Biography information for Sir Peter Bottomley","Worthing West","Sir Peter Bottomley","10212"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418743","Northern Ireland Office","false","2015-09-21","<p>The Northern Ireland Office (NIO) has provided a Shared FOI Service along with the Wales Office since September 2014. The FOI Team consists of one full-time member of NIO staff and three part-time members of Wales Office staff, who together contribute 0.4 FTE (full-time equivalent). Man hours spent on this area of work are not measured on a monthly basis; the Departments have allocated 1.4 staff who are responsible for this area of work.</p><p> </p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace",,"2015-09-21T14:09:58.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418743/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418743/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418743/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2015-09-14","Northern Ireland Office: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, how many hours her Department spent on processing freedom of information requests in each of the last 24 months.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","10229"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418744","Prime Minister","false","2015-09-17","<p>I have nothing further to add to my response to the hon. Member of 11 September 2015, UIN <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2015-09-04/8501/" target="_blank">8501</a>.</p>","Witney","Mr David Cameron",,"2015-09-17T12:47:49.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418744/answer","Biography information for Mr David Cameron","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418744/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418744/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2015-09-14","Members: Surveillance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, pursuant to the Answer of 11 September 2015 to Question 8501, whether the Wilson Doctrine applies in the same way to Members of the Scottish Parliament as it applies to hon. Members and Members of the House of Lords.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","10138"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418745","Scotland Office","false","2015-09-18","<p>Processing Freedom of Information requests is an integral part of civil servants' responsibilities. The number of hours spent on this activity is not separately identifiable.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2015-09-18T12:33:30.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418745/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418745/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418745/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2015-09-14","Scotland Office: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how many hours his Department spent on processing freedom of information requests in each of the last 24 months.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","10230"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418746","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-17","<p>The Maritime &amp; Coastguard Agency (MCA) carries out regular surveys of the wreck of the SS Richard Montgomery. These are generally multibeam sonar surveys and, in recent years, they have also included laser scanning of those parts of the wreck’s structure which are visible above the waterline. Survey reports, and background information about the wreck, are published at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-ss-richard-montgomery-information-and-survey-reports" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-ss-richard-montgomery-information-and-survey-reports</a></p><p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p>In addition, Medway Port Authority guards the wreck under contract to the MCA. The Authority provides: 24 hour surveillance of the wreck, both visually and by radar; patrols of the area around the wreck; and an initial response to any potential incursions.</p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-09-17T12:00:21.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418746/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418746/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418746/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-14","SS Richard Montgomery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans his Department has to monitor the condition and safety of the SS Richard Montgomery; and when he plans to publicise the results of such monitoring.","false","Biography information for Gordon Henderson","Sittingbourne and Sheppey","Gordon Henderson","10148"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418747","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-17","<p>I fully support the decision to recruit a new Director of the United Kingdom Ship Register within the Maritime and Coastguard Agency. Creating this position is an immediate and positive response to a recommendation in Lord Mountevans’ Maritime Growth Study Report published on 7 September 2015 at the start of London International Shipping Week. The appointment will be made as soon as possible on the basis of an open and fair competition for this Senior Civil Service role. There is no deadline by which that appointment must be made.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-09-17T12:16:14.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418747/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418747/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418747/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-14","Shipping: Registration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions he has had with the Maritime and Coastguard Agency on the appointment of a new head of the UK Shipping Register; and whether there is a deadline by which that vacancy must be filled.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","10124"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418748","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-17","<p>A Business Case with a future operating model for the Maritime and Coastguard Agency’s ship survey and inspection operation will be considered soon by the Department for Transport and subsequently by HM Treasury.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Consultation will follow and the Survey and Inspection Transformation Programme (SITP) proposals and plans will be published through GOV.UK in due course.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-09-17T12:06:12.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418748/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418748/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418748/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-14","Maritime and Coastguard Agency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he plans for the Maritime and Coastguard Agency's Survey and Inspection Transformation Programme to be launched; and how he plans to publicise that programme using his Department's website.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","10125"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418749","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-17","<p>The Maritime and Coastguard Agency (MCA) carry out a maximum four year cycle of audits of the Overseas Territory (OT)/Crown Dependency (CD) Administrations, the scope of which is covered in the signed Memorandum of Understanding (MOU) between the UK Government and the individual Government of the OTs and CDs for the operation of their British shipping register. The MOU contains an obligation to ensure that all vessels registered, that are subject to safe manning criteria, are properly crewed and certificated to International Maritime Organization’s (IMO) standards.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The MCA surveyors also carry out targeted inspections of Red Ensign Group (REG) ships visiting UK ports under the Merchant Shipping Act. If examples of a failure to comply are identified, the MCA has at its disposal the same control measures as for Port State Control, i.e. detention, prohibition notices, improvement notices and defect rectification. Findings of these inspections are fed back to the MCA to follow-up with the relevant REG administration.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-09-17T12:10:17.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418749/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418749/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418749/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-14","Shipping: Crew","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps the Maritime and Coastguard Agency is taking to ensure that members of the Red Ensign Group comply with the safe manning levels recommended by that agency.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","10123"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418750","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-17","<p>There are no prescriptive regulations requiring certain numbers of crew for ship types, trade routes or types of cargo. The arrangements we have in place are explained in full in Merchant Shipping Notice (MSN) 1868.</p><p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p>Vessels of more than 500 GT are required to hold a Safe Manning Document.</p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-09-17T12:59:15.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418750/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418750/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418750/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-14","Shipping: Crew","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what arrangements are in place for determining safe manning levels on UK merchant ships for each (a) classification of ship, (b) trade route and (c) type of cargo.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","10126"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418751","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-18","<p>The Maritime and Coastguard Agency (MCA) does not have the figures for amendments to Safe Manning Documents requested dating back to 1998. However, the following figures are available from 2010 relating to all changes.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>2010 – 94</p><p> </p><p>2011 – 67</p><p> </p><p>2012 – 68</p><p> </p><p>2013 – 52</p><p> </p><p>2014 – 139</p><p> </p><p>2015 – 49 (to date)</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The vast majority of these changes have been changes to names of ships or companies. A small number relate to changes in engine power or crew numbers.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-09-18T09:01:34.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418751/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418751/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418751/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-14","Shipping: Crew","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, on how many occasions the Maritime and Coastguard Agency changed the safe manning certificate for merchant ships on the UK Registry in each year since 1998.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","10127"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418752","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-17","<p>There are no plans to amend legislation on minimum safe manning levels on merchant ships to require the Maritime and Coastguard Agency (MCA) to consult maritime trade unions when a shipowner applies for a change to a vessel’s safe manning document.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>However, under the current regulations MSN 1868 Section 6 ‘Consultation and Schedule’ requires owners to:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>‘…. consult with the Master, seafarers, seafarers’ representatives (where applicable) and the MCA on their proposed manning levels and draw up a schedule [of manning] accordingly…. If agreement cannot be reached ….the MCA will consider the views put forward and if necessary require the schedule to be revised. Where disagreement occurs it may be necessary to arrange a practical demonstration of the crew’s ability to carry out the essential tasks in the context of the principles of safe manning.’</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-09-17T12:55:20.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418752/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418752/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418752/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-14","Shipping: Crew","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will amend legislation on minimum safe manning levels on merchant ships to require the Maritime and Coastguard Agency to consult maritime trade unions when a shipowner applies for a change to a vessel's safe manning certificate.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","10128"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418753","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-18","<p>The Government is currently considering the large amount of very detailed analysis contained in the Airports Commission’s final report, including its examination of the costs and financing of the schemes, before taking any decisions on next steps.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-09-18T09:09:13.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418753/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418753/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418753/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-14","Heathrow Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what work his Department is giving to the (a) public funding requirements of and (b) potential state aid issues related to a new runway at Heathrow airport.","false","Biography information for Mike Kane","Wythenshawe and Sale East","Mike Kane","10131"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418754","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-21","<p>Network Rail monitors and assesses the capacity of its rail network as part of the long term planning obligations set in its license conditions, and publishes this information.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-09-21T10:26:41.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418754/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418754/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418754/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-14","Railways","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the capacity of the rail network to meet future demand; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","10145"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418755","Home Office","false","2015-09-17","<p>The enforcement of speeding limits is an operational matter for the police. Under the Road Traffic Regulation Act (1984), any driver using a vehicle for an emergency service purpose can claim an exemption from speeding penalties if complying with the speed limits would have hindered the purpose for which the vehicle was being used.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-09-17T11:26:56.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418755/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418755/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418755/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-14","Emergency Services: Driving Offences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what plans she has to reduce the number of speeding tickets issued to ambulances and other emergency vehicles.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","10116"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418756","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-21","<p>Processing Freedom of Information requests is an integral part of civil servants' responsibilities. The number of hours spent on this activity is not separately identifiable.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-09-21T10:31:05.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418756/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418756/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418756/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-14","Department for Transport: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many hours his Department spent on processing freedom of information requests in each of the last 24 months.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","10231"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418757","Wales Office","false","2015-09-17","<p>The Wales Office has a shared service arrangement with the Northern Ireland Office for the provision of FOI services. There is one full time FOI manager employed by the Northern Ireland Office supported by three people from the Wales Office on a part time basis (0.4 full time equivalent staff). The FOI Team does not record the number of hours spent on processing FOI requests.</p><p> </p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2015-09-17T09:57:46.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418757/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418757/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418757/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2015-09-14","Wales Office: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, how many hours his Department spent on processing freedom of information requests in each of the last 24 months.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","10233"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418758","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-17","<p>Processing Freedom of Information requests is an integral part of civil servants' responsibilities. As such the number of hours spent on this activity is not separately identifiable.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-09-17T10:25:56.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418758/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418758/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418758/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-09-14","Department for Work and Pensions: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many hours his Department spent on processing freedom of information requests in each of the last 24 months.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","10234"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418759","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-17","<p /> <p>The information requested is available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk</a></p><p> </p><p>Guidance on how to extract the information required can be found at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started---SuperWEB2.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started---SuperWEB2.html</a></p><p> </p><p>To obtain the information divide the yearly amounts requested by 52.18 to give the weekly amount of housing benefit in payment. A search can then be made in Stat-Xplore for the number of cases with those weekly amounts in payment.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-09-17T11:33:26.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418759/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418759/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418759/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-09-14","Housing Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many households were in receipt of housing benefit totalling up to (a) £10,000, (b) £25,000, (c) £50,000, (d) £75,000 and (e) £100,000 per annum in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","10106"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418760","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-17","<p /> <p>Jobcentre Plus uses a range of innovative approaches to help older claimants back to work. Training to help unemployed people find work is available to benefit claimants of all ages.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, we have introduced a number of initiatives to support older people including the introduction of Jobcentre Plus Older Claimant Champions and the launch of the work experience and sector based work academy pilots that will support 3,000 claimants. We are trialling career reviews and digital support in two Jobcentre Plus districts.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-09-17T13:40:25.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418760/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418760/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418760/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-09-14","Unemployment: Older People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps he is taking to help older unemployed people to retrain.","false","Biography information for Dr Tania Mathias","Twickenham","Dr Tania Mathias","10176"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418761","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-17","<p /> <p>Data on Personal Independence Payment (PIP) registrations, clearances and award rates, at regional level, are available on Gov.UK and were most recently updated on 16 September: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/personal-independence-payment-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/personal-independence-payment-statistics</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The information requested in relation to appeals is not available and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost. Information on PIP mandatory reconsiderations has been published with the PIP data (earlier link refers) and data for PIP appeals are published by the Ministry of Justice as part of their quarterly Tribunal statistics: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/tribunals-statistics#social-security-and-child-support-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/tribunals-statistics#social-security-and-child-support-statistics</a></p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-09-17T10:15:16.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418761/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418761/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418761/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-09-14","Personal Independence Payment: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people in Scotland have (a) applied for personal independence payments (PIPs), (b) been refused PIPs and (c) been refused PIPs and subsequently had that decision overturned on appeal; and how many such decisions overturned on appeal were challenged by his Department.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","10214"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418762","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-17","<p>The Government plans to respond to this consultation by the end of the year.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-09-17T14:16:12.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418762/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418762/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418762/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-09-14","Occupational Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when he plans to publish the Government's response to his Department's consultation on changes to the Occupational Pension (Investment) regulations.","false","Biography information for Neil Carmichael","Stroud","Neil Carmichael","10183"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418912","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-17","<p>Government is committed to supporting the oil and gas industry, which is vital to our energy supply and supports around 375,000 UK jobs. We recognise the challenges resulting from lower oil prices, and those highlighted in the Oil and Gas Authority’s Call to Action report. The Oil and Gas Authority is working with groups such as the Scottish Energy Jobs Taskforce, to encourage companies to consider all possible alternatives to redundancy and retain capability needed for the future.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-09-17T14:16:57.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418912/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418912/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418912/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-14","Offshore Industry: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what assessment she has made of the implications for her policy of (a) the findings of the Oil and Gas Authority's Call to Action report, published on 25 February 2015, on employment in the oil and gas industry and (b) that report's other findings; and what steps she plans to take to support employment in that industry.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart McDonald","901438"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419265","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-21","<p>Progress is being made towards reaching an international climate change agreement in Paris and there is political will for a deal:</p><p>So far 60 countries (including all G7 countries) responsible for 62% of global emissions have submitted their emission reduction commitments;</p><p>G7 Leaders are committed to an ambitious climate package to be agreed in Paris and to the need for strong language on future ambition and a commitment to long term decarbonisation and;</p><p>Progress is being made on climate finance. Last week, I co-facilitated the finance discussions at the Paris Ministerial meetings and we made progress with other developed countries on how we count mobilised climate finance towards delivering the $100bn 2020 target.</p><p> </p><p>I will continue to play a strong and constructive role leading up to and during the Paris COP.</p><p> </p>","Hastings and Rye","Amber Rudd",,"2015-09-21T14:18:11.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419265/answer","Biography information for Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419265/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419265/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-14","Climate Change Convention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what recent progress has been made towards reaching an international climate change agreement in Paris in 2015.","false","Biography information for John Cryer","Leyton and Wanstead","John Cryer","901437"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419266","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-21","<p>My Department recently published updated analysis on estimated capacity of key renewable technologies in 2020/21, compared to the 2013 Electricity Market Reform Delivery Plan. Even with proposed cost control measures, we are on course to meet the Delivery Plan ranges and to deliver at least 30% of the UK's electricity from renewable sources by 2020. In 2014, nearly a fifth of the UK's electricity came from renewables.</p>","Hastings and Rye","Amber Rudd",,"2015-09-21T14:18:25.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419266/answer","Biography information for Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419266/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419266/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-14","Renewable Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what progress has been made in achieving the level of renewable deployment set out in her Department's  energy market review implementation plan.","false","Biography information for Antoinette Sandbach","Eddisbury","Antoinette Sandbach","901444"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419267","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-17","<p>The Feed-in Tariff scheme has been hugely successful in encouraging the generation of low carbon energy for homes and businesses and we will continue to incentivise this growing sector.</p><p>On heat, the Renewable Heat Incentive encourages the installation of renewable heating in place of fossil fuels in homes and non-domestic buildings. This includes air-source heat pumps; deep geothermal; energy from waste; and a wide range of other technologies.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-09-17T12:51:40.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419267/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419267/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419267/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-14","Renewable Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what steps she is taking to incentivise the use of renewable energy in businesses and homes.","false","Biography information for Jo Churchill","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill","901448"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419268","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-17","<p>His Rt. Hon. and Noble Friend Lord Hutton’s report on Public Service Pensions was adopted by the Government in 2013 and set out the direction of travel for all public sector pensions.</p><p>We are now considering, with the Nuclear Decommissioning Authority, what steps we can take to implement the public sector reforms bearing in mind the unique complexities and the vital importance of our nuclear decommissioning programme.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-09-17T12:53:40.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419268/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419268/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419268/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-14","Nuclear Decommissioning Authority: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, whether the Nuclear Decommissioning Authority's pension reform proposals form part of  a wider workforce reform package.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","901454"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418375","Home Office","false","2015-09-21","<p>The Joint Terrorism Analysis Centre (JTAC) supports the Government and law enforcement agencies by analysing and assessing all intelligence relating to international terrorism at home and overseas. It would not be appropriate to comment on those assessments, but the Government can give an assurance that JTAC continuously assesses the threat to the UK and its interests from international terrorism in whatever form that threat takes.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-09-21T15:51:03.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418375/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418375/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418375/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-11","Undocumented Migrants: Calais","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the number of possible jihadists amongst the migrants at Calais attempting to enter the United Kingdom.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL2169"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418376","Home Office","false","2015-09-21","<p>The Joint Terrorism Analysis Centre (JTAC) supports the Government and law enforcement agencies by analysing and assessing all intelligence relating to international terrorism at home and overseas. It would not be appropriate to comment on those assessments, but the Government can give an assurance that JTAC continuously assesses the threat to the UK and its interests from international terrorism in whatever form that threat takes.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-09-21T15:51:15.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418376/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418376/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418376/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-11","Undocumented Migrants: EU Countries","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of whether there are jihadists amongst the migrants entering Hungary, Austria and Germany.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL2170"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418377","Home Office","false","2015-09-22","<p>Border Force uses a range of methods to detect and deter those seeking to enter the UK using stolen passports. This includes the use of advanced technology to identify those attempting to travel to the UK on lost or stolen documentation. Immigration Enforcement operates a network of overseas liaison officers whose role includes working with transport operators to identify imposters and prevent them from travelling to the UK. At the UK border, Border Force Officers, with expertise in forgery and imposter detection, carry out comprehensive checks on all passengers arriving at passport control to establish authenticity and whether the passenger is the rightful holder.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-09-22T14:36:35.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418377/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418377/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418377/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-11","Undocumented Migrants","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to detect people from Iraq, Pakistan, Palestine and Albania using stolen Syrian passports to enter the United Kingdom.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL2171"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418378","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-21","<p>The British Government is opposed to the death penalty in all circumstances and calls on all states to adopt a moratorium on the use of the death penalty in accordance with UN General Assembly resolution 186 adopted in December 2014. This is part of the process towards complete abolition. The UK’s own experience showed that the death penalty did not deter crime, and miscarriages of justice were irreversible and irreparable. Where we judge that an execution is incompatible with international law or marks a backward step, we raise our concerns privately and publicly.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-09-21T14:45:43.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418378/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418378/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418378/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-11","Capital Punishment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the moral and philosophical case for them making representations to foreign governments on the use of the death penalty in their countries.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL2172"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418379","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-09-22","<p>The UK is committed to protecting wildlife in accordance with the EU Habitats and Birds Directives through domestic legislation and the designation of Special Sites of Scientific Interest, Special Protection Areas and Special Areas of Conservation.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Biodiversity is a devolved matter. In England, we will take forward our manifesto commitment to produce a 25 year strategy for the environment, which will include biodiversity. Over the next five years we will be investing more than £3 billion in environmental outcomes as part of the Rural Development Programme for England (2014-2020). This funding will enhance England’s countryside, enabling us, among other things, to clean up our rivers and lakes, protect drystone walls and hedges, and help birds, bees and other species to thrive.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Biodiversity is one of the main objectives in the new Countryside Stewardship Scheme, to be funded under the Rural Development Programme. The Wild Pollinator and Farm Wildlife Package options within the scheme will be of particular benefit to wild pollinators, farmland birds and other species.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We will ensure that our public forests and woodland are kept in trust for the nation and plant another 11 million trees.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Since 2010, we have created over 67,000 hectares of priority habitats such as arable field margins, wetlands and woodlands. We have also maintained over 95% of our Sites of Special Scientific Interest – our most important sites for wildlife – in favourable or recovering condition and put in place Marine Conservation Zones to supplement the stretches of our sea that are already marine protected areas.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>UK Overseas Territory (OT) Governments are constitutionally responsible for the protection and conservation of their natural environments. The UK Government cherishes the environmental assets of the OTs and we work in partnership with OT Governments to identify where our support can be most effective, including through access to expertise, technical advice and training and through the Overseas Territory Environment and Climate Fund (Darwin Plus).</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Through Darwin Plus, the UK Government has committed approximately £5.2 million since 2012 to help protect the natural environment in the OTs. Projects currently being funded range from conserving four keystone tree species in St Helena, to an assessment of the conservation status of the endangered Atlantic yellow-nosed albatross on Tristan da Cunha.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Joint UK Government and South Atlantic OTs funding also supports a co-ordinating post based in the Falkland Islands to help meet obligations arising from the Agreement on the Conservation of Albatrosses and Petrels and to assist with the planning and implementation of albatross and petrel conservation work.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble","HL2174","2015-09-22T10:55:48.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418379/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418379/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418379/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-09-11","Birds: Conservation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to reverse the decline in wild bird populations in the United Kingdom and the Overseas Territories.","false","Biography information for Lord Jones of Cheltenham",,"Lord Jones of Cheltenham","HL2173"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418380","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-09-22","<p>The UK is committed to protecting wildlife in accordance with the EU Habitats and Birds Directives through domestic legislation and the designation of Special Sites of Scientific Interest, Special Protection Areas and Special Areas of Conservation.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Biodiversity is a devolved matter. In England, we will take forward our manifesto commitment to produce a 25 year strategy for the environment, which will include biodiversity. Over the next five years we will be investing more than £3 billion in environmental outcomes as part of the Rural Development Programme for England (2014-2020). This funding will enhance England’s countryside, enabling us, among other things, to clean up our rivers and lakes, protect drystone walls and hedges, and help birds, bees and other species to thrive.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Biodiversity is one of the main objectives in the new Countryside Stewardship Scheme, to be funded under the Rural Development Programme. The Wild Pollinator and Farm Wildlife Package options within the scheme will be of particular benefit to wild pollinators, farmland birds and other species.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We will ensure that our public forests and woodland are kept in trust for the nation and plant another 11 million trees.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Since 2010, we have created over 67,000 hectares of priority habitats such as arable field margins, wetlands and woodlands. We have also maintained over 95% of our Sites of Special Scientific Interest – our most important sites for wildlife – in favourable or recovering condition and put in place Marine Conservation Zones to supplement the stretches of our sea that are already marine protected areas.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>UK Overseas Territory (OT) Governments are constitutionally responsible for the protection and conservation of their natural environments. The UK Government cherishes the environmental assets of the OTs and we work in partnership with OT Governments to identify where our support can be most effective, including through access to expertise, technical advice and training and through the Overseas Territory Environment and Climate Fund (Darwin Plus).</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Through Darwin Plus, the UK Government has committed approximately £5.2 million since 2012 to help protect the natural environment in the OTs. Projects currently being funded range from conserving four keystone tree species in St Helena, to an assessment of the conservation status of the endangered Atlantic yellow-nosed albatross on Tristan da Cunha.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Joint UK Government and South Atlantic OTs funding also supports a co-ordinating post based in the Falkland Islands to help meet obligations arising from the Agreement on the Conservation of Albatrosses and Petrels and to assist with the planning and implementation of albatross and petrel conservation work.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble","HL2173","2015-09-22T10:55:48.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418380/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418380/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418380/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-09-11","Nature Conservation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to protect and conserve all forms of wild flora and fauna in the United Kingdom and the Overseas Territories, including rare and endangered species.","false","Biography information for Lord Jones of Cheltenham",,"Lord Jones of Cheltenham","HL2174"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418381","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-09-22","<p>UK Overseas Territory (OT) Governments are constitutionally responsible for the protection and conservation of their natural environments. Through the UK Government-funded Overseas Territory Environment and Climate Fund (Darwin Plus) we have committed approximately £5.2 million since 2012 to supporting environment projects in the OTs. A number of these have helped to conserve penguins.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Darwin Plus has funded projects to create a regional database of penguin tracking data, population analysis and modelling and to deploy autonomous camera units to monitor penguin populations in the British Antarctic Territory and South Georgia and South Sandwich Islands.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In addition, the Foreign and Commonwealth Office recently funded a project led by the Royal Society for the Protection of Birds to carry out the first ever stocktake of species in the OTs. The study, completed between January 2013 and March 2014, with further work in 2015, brought together all known species records and conservation assessments. Although only a few OTs have permanent penguin populations, it found that the islands of the OTs include more penguins than any other nation on earth, holding an estimated 36% of the world’s population of southern rockhopper penguins and 34% of gentoo penguins.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2015-09-22T10:56:10.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418381/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418381/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418381/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-09-11","Penguins: British Overseas Territories","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the population trends of penguins in the Overseas Territories.","false","Biography information for Lord Jones of Cheltenham",,"Lord Jones of Cheltenham","HL2175"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418382","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-09-17","<p>Defra has published on gov.uk the total operational and policing costs to Defra for the licensed culls in Somerset and Gloucestershire in 2013 and 2014, and total number of badgers culled. We do not have a breakdown of operational or policing costs for each individual badger killed.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2015-09-17T16:28:51.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418382/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418382/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418382/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-09-11","Bovine Tuberculosis: Disease Control","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what has been the cost of operational and policing requirements for each badger killed under the culling programme.","false","Biography information for Lord Jones of Cheltenham",,"Lord Jones of Cheltenham","HL2176"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418383","Department of Health","false","2015-09-17","<p>Many extractions are already carried out on a day case basis; whether the extraction is carried out as a day case or requires an overnight admission is a matter for the clinicians involved.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>NHS England has advised that NHS Lancashire and Greater Manchester have for a number of years commissioned day case surgery as well as overnight admission for children who require a full clearance of deciduous teeth under general anaesthetic.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2015-09-17T16:27:15.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418383/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418383/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418383/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-11","Dental Services: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Prior of Brampton on 27 July (HL1635), whether they have plans to introduce day surgery appointments for the clearance or extraction of deciduous teeth under general anaesthetic.","false","Biography information for Baroness Gardner of Parkes",,"Baroness Gardner of Parkes","HL2177"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418384","Department of Health","false","2015-09-21","<p>It has been the policy of successive governments that decisions on water fluoridation are best taken locally. The Health and Social Care Act 2012 gave powers to upper tier and unitary local authorities to make proposals in relation to fluoridation.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In 2014 Public Health England published a water fluoridation health monitoring report which showed lower levels of tooth decay in areas with water fluoridation.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Public Health England has also, in 2014, published an evidence informed toolkit for local authorities to support them in planning, reviewing and commissioning oral health improvement interventions for children and young people, including the potential role of water fluoridation.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2015-09-21T15:12:30.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418384/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418384/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418384/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-11","Fluoride: Drinking Water","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have plans to make representations to Manchester City Council to give further consideration to fluoridation of the water supply in Greater Manchester; and whether any such representations will take account of the lower level of tooth decay amongst children in Birmingham, where the water supply has been fluoridated since 1964.","false","Biography information for Baroness Gardner of Parkes",,"Baroness Gardner of Parkes","HL2178"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418385","Department of Health","false","2015-09-22","<p>Neither the Department nor NHS England have made an assessment of the number of lives that might be saved per annum from licensing bisphosphonates for the treatment of early post-menopausal breast cancer.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Doctors can already prescribe a drug outside its licensed indications where they judge it to be the most clinically appropriate treatment for an individual patient.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL2180","2015-09-22T10:19:17.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418385/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418385/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418385/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-11","Breast Cancer: Drugs","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the number of lives that might be saved per annum from licensing bisphosphonates for the treatment of early post-menopausal breast cancer.","false","Biography information for Lord MacKenzie of Culkein",,"Lord MacKenzie of Culkein","HL2179"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418386","Department of Health","false","2015-09-22","<p>Neither the Department nor NHS England have made an assessment of the number of lives that might be saved per annum from licensing bisphosphonates for the treatment of early post-menopausal breast cancer.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Doctors can already prescribe a drug outside its licensed indications where they judge it to be the most clinically appropriate treatment for an individual patient.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL2179","2015-09-22T10:19:18.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418386/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418386/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418386/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-11","Breast Cancer: Drugs","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether doctors are free to prescribe bisphosphonates in the treatment of early stage breast cancer despite the fact that it is not presently licensed for that purpose.","false","Biography information for Lord MacKenzie of Culkein",,"Lord MacKenzie of Culkein","HL2180"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418387","Department of Health","false","2015-09-22","<p>The net ingredient cost of prescription items dispensed in the community in England for bisphosphonates<sup>1</sup> in 2014, was £16.813 million<sup>2</sup>.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In secondary care, the cost in 2014 was £35.841 million<sup>3</sup>.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) has published clinical guidelines on early and locally advanced breast cancer and advanced breast cancer, published in February 2009, and familial breast cancer published in June 2013. NICE periodically reviews its guidance to take account of new and emerging evidence.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>A copy of these clinical guidelines are attached.</p><p> </p><p><em> </em></p><p> </p><p><sup>1 </sup>Bisphosphonates are defined as those included in paragraph 6.6.2 (Bisphosphonates and other drugs affecting bone metabolism) of the British National Formulary (BNF) but excluding denosumab and strontium ranelate.</p><p> </p><p><sup>2 </sup>Source: Prescription Cost Analysis (PCA) provided by the Health and Social Care Information Centre</p><p> </p><p><sup>3 </sup>Source: Hospital Pharmacy Audit Index (HPAI) provided by IMS Health</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2015-09-22T10:20:06.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418387/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418387/answer","HL2181 Cost ofbisphosphonates to the NHS.doc attachment 1.pdf ; HL2181 Cost ofbisphosphonates to the NHS.doc attachment 2.pdf ; HL2181 Cost ofbisphosphonates to the NHS.doc attachment 3.pdf","HL2181 Cost ofbisphosphonates to the NHS.doc attachment 1.pdf ; HL2181 Cost ofbisphosphonates to the NHS.doc attachment 2.pdf ; HL2181 Cost ofbisphosphonates to the NHS.doc attachment 3.pdf","Early and locally advanced breast cancer guideline ; Advanced breast cancer guidelines ; Familial breast cancer guidelines","Early and locally advanced breast cancer guideline ; Advanced breast cancer guidelines ; Familial breast cancer guidelines","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418387/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-11","Breast Cancer: Drugs","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the cost to the National Health Service of bisphosphonates and whether they will take steps to encourage the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence to consider the evidence base for the prescription of these drugs in treatment of early stage breast cancer.","false","Biography information for Lord MacKenzie of Culkein",,"Lord MacKenzie of Culkein","HL2181"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418388","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-16","<p>UK Trade and Investment has a duty to British businesses to provide them with all of the advice and information they need to succeed in foreign markets. Human rights guidance is a core part of that. The UK National Action Plan for implementation of the UN Guiding Principles on Business and Human Rights, entitled &quot;Good Business&quot;, sets out what the Government will do and what it expects of business in respecting human rights throughout their operations.</p><p>The Government is working with the Government of Malawi and British companies to encourage greater bilateral trade and investment. In their meetings with British companies in Malawi, officials at the British High Commission in Lilongwe have raised the importance of human rights and corporate responsibility.</p>","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps",,"2015-09-16T14:44:51.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418388/answer","Biography information for Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418388/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418388/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-11","Overseas Companies: Malawi","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he is taking to ensure British companies and investors in Malawi respect human rights in that country.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","9960"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418389","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-21","<p>My Rt. hon. Friend the Chancellor of the Exchequer announced in December 2014 a long-term commitment to investment in science infrastructure of £1.1bn per annum in real terms to 2021.</p><p> </p><p>Decisions on the amount and allocation of research resource funding beyond 2015/16 will be made during the Spending Review.</p><p> </p><p>We cannot pre-judge the Spending Review outcome.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-09-21T15:51:18.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418389/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418389/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418389/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-11","Science: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether the Government plans to reduce its spending on science in the next three years.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","9969"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418390","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-09-16","<p>As outlined in the Digital Communications Infrastructure Strategy, the government has commissioned an independent review of the use of IPv6 in the UK. We are in the final stages of this review and the outcomes will inform future policy making in this area. We intend to publish the outcome of the Review in due course.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-09-16T14:15:01.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418390/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418390/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418390/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-09-11","Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment he has made of the extent of the adoption of IPv6; and what steps he is taking to promote such adoption.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","10008"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418391","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-06","<p>I have no such plans.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-10-06T13:26:17.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418391/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418391/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418391/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-11","Consumer Rights Act 2015","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what plans he has to bring forward legislative proposals to (a) amend and (b) repeal sections of the Consumer Rights Act 2015.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","10062"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418392","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-21","<p>While HM Revenue and Customs has been working cases involving Modern Day Slavery for some time, data has not been collected for this period.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","10053 ; 10055","2015-09-21T12:38:22.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418392/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418392/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418392/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-11","Slavery","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many enforcement actions were undertaken by HM Revenue and Customs in each of the last three years involving unlawful deductions made more than two years before an unlawful deductions claim was brought by a victim of modern slavery.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","10054"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418393","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-21","<p>While HM Revenue and Customs has been working cases involving Modern Day Slavery for some time, data has not been collected for this period.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","10053 ; 10054","2015-09-21T12:38:22.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418393/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418393/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418393/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-11","Pay: Deductions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many enforcement actions were undertaken by HM Revenue and Customs in each of the last three years involving unlawful deductions made more than two years before an unlawful deductions claim was brought.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","10055"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418394","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-21","<p>The Government is determined that everyone who is entitled to the National Minimum Wage (NMW) receives it. Anyone who feels they have been underpaid NMW should contact the Acas helpline on 0300 123 1100. HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) review all complaints that are referred to them.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>There are currently 232 staff working in National Minimum Wage for HMRC, up from 171 at the start of 2014/15. The Government takes the enforcement of the National Minimum Wage very seriously and has increased funding from £8m in 2013/14 to £13.2m in 2015/16 allowing for around 278 staff to be in post by the end of 2015/16.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-09-21T12:45:17.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418394/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418394/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418394/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-11","Revenue and Customs: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many permanent staff members are employed by HM Revenue and Customs to undertake national minimum wage inspection activity.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","10050"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418395","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-21","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) have appointed a Modern Slavery Strategic Lead who is working across the department and with other local and national agencies to coordinate operational activity. The lead sits in Enforcement and Compliance in HMRC, reporting to the Director General Enforcement and Compliance at a senior level.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-09-21T10:35:02.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418395/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418395/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418395/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-11","Slavery","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, who he has appointed as his Department's Modern Slavery Strategic Lead.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","10051"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418396","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-21","<p>HM Revenue and Customs’ (HMRC) Modern Slavery Strategic Lead works closely with all appropriate government and non-government partners at both a national, strategic level and a local, operational level.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>At a national level, HMRC is represented on all the cross-government Modern Slavery governance bodies. More locally, the Modern Slavery Strategic Lead represents HMRC on local anti-slavery partnership groups, which include non-governmental organisations.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-09-21T10:36:33.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418396/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418396/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418396/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-11","Slavery","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what processes are in place for liaison between his Department's Modern Slavery Strategic Lead and key stakeholders in civil society.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","10052"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418397","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-21","<p>While HM Revenue and Customs has been working cases involving Modern Day Slavery for some time, data has not been collected for this period.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","10054 ; 10055","2015-09-21T12:38:22.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418397/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418397/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418397/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-11","Slavery","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many enforcement actions were undertaken by HM Revenue and Customs in each of the last three years involving a victim of modern slavery.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","10053"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418398","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-16","<p>As with any new EU legislation, HM Treasury engaged in discussions with the European Commission and other EU member states during the negotiation of the Deposit Guarantee Schemes Directive, and following its adoption in order to manage the transposition effectively. HM Treasury laid a statutory instrument to ensure that UK depositors would not be exposed to a sudden reduction in the level of protection to which they are entitled from the Financial Services Compensation Scheme (FSCS).</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>FSCS compensation is funded by levies on regulated financial services firms, within a limit which is set by the Financial Conduct Authority and Prudential Regulation Authority.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-09-16T16:44:10.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418398/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418398/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418398/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-11","Financial Services: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions he has had with his EU counterparts and the European Commission on retaining the level of UK bank deposit guarantees at £85,000; and what estimate he has made of the level of funds set aside for such guarantees in (a) 2015 and (b) 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr David Nuttall","Bury North","Mr David Nuttall","10016"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418399","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-17","<p>Large investment funds effectively comprise the investments of individuals, whether via their pension funds, insurance contracts, or other savings and investment products. The decision to invest in companies’ shares directly, or indirectly through a fund, is a matter for individual investors.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government has taken a variety of steps to encourage individual saving, and retail investment in shares in particular. For example, we have:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>- Reduced the starting rate of income tax for savings;</p><p> </p><p>- Increased the maximum annual amount which can be invested in an Individual Savings Account (ISA) to £15,240 in the 2015-16 tax year, and provided savers with greater flexibility to withdraw their money and put it back in to an ISA within the same year, without losing their tax benefits;</p><p> </p><p>- Introduced, from April 2016, a new tax-free Personal Savings Allowance of £1,000 (or £500 for higher rate taxpayers) of interest earned on savings (taking 95 per cent of taxpayers out of savings tax altogether) as well as a new £5,000 tax-free dividend allowance for all taxpayers;</p><p> </p><p>- Allowed shares from growth markets such as the Alternative Investment Market (AIM) to be held in ISAs - making investment in the growth markets easier;</p><p> </p><p>- Abolished stamp duty on AIM shares, attracting further investment into growing companies and reducing the cost of raising capital for those companies.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-09-17T10:09:22.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418399/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418399/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418399/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-11","Shareholders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will take steps to address the disparity between the number of shares owned by individuals and large investment funds.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","9998"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418400","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-21","<p>Treasury Ministers have meetings with senior officials within HM Revenue and Customs on a regular basis as part of the process of policy development and delivery.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-09-21T10:33:22.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418400/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418400/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418400/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-11","Revenue and Customs: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions he has had with HM Revenue and Customs on the process for target-setting for call answering times at the income tax helpline.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","9957"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418401","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-17","<p /> <p>The Government set out its assessment of the impacts of the policies in the Welfare Reform and Work Bill on 20th July. A link to the impact assessment is included.</p><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/documents/impact-assessments/IA15-006.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/documents/impact-assessments/IA15-006.pdf</a></p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","10147","2015-09-17T10:21:30.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418401/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418401/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418401/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-09-11","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the effect of reductions in the benefit cap on local authority budgets.","false","Biography information for Dawn Butler","Brent Central","Dawn Butler","9965"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418402","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-09-21","<p>Where a material consideration is raised through public consultation, the weight to be given to that consideration is a question for the decision maker and will depend on the circumstances of the specfic case (subject to the test of legal reasonableness).</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-09-21T13:05:16.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418402/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418402/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418402/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-09-11","Planning Permission: Public Opinion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether his Department issues guidance to local planning authorities on the weight to place on (a) individual public responses and (b) overall local public opinion when processing planning applications.","false","Biography information for Mr Nicholas Brown","Newcastle upon Tyne East","Mr Nicholas Brown","9994"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418403","Home Office","false","2015-09-16","<p>Licensing authorities have powers under the Licensing Act 2003 to restrict the hours in which alcohol is sold, if it is appropriate for the promotion of the licensing objectives. Decisions are based on individual consideration of each premises application, as appropriate for the promotion of the licensing objectives and in line with the licensing authority’s statement of licensing policy.</p><p>Early morning alcohol restriction orders (EMRO) allow a licensing authority to restrict the sale of alcohol between midnight and 6am. EMROs are designed to address recurring problems such as high levels of alcohol-related crime and disorder in specific areas at specific times; serious public nuisance; and other instances of alcohol-related anti-social behaviour which is not directly attributable to specific premises. Licensing authorities may decide to implement a Cumulative Impact Policy (CIP) where an exceptional number of licensed premises concentrated in one area have a cumulative impact on the promotion of the licensing objectives in that area. The CIP creates a rebuttable presumption that applications for premises licences which are likely to add to the existing cumulative impact will normally be refused or subject to certain limitations. The Government keeps these powers under review, but there are currently no plans to create additional new powers for licensing authorities.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-09-16T12:21:41.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418403/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418403/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418403/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-11","Off-licences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what powers local authorities currently have to restrict the hours during which off-licences can sell alcohol; and whether the Government has plans to devolve further such powers to local authorities","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","10056"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418404","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-09-21","<p>The Government will increase funding for Discretionary Housing Payments to a total of £800 million across the Parliament to enable local authorities to help people who need extra support with housing costs. As in previous years, funding will be allocated to local authorities based on local pressures, including housing benefit caseload and the effects of reforms in Housing Benefit. We consider these local impacts each year during our allocation of Discretionary Housing Payment funds, and this will continue.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2015-09-21T13:52:10.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418404/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418404/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418404/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-09-11","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will take steps to provide additional support to local authorities in areas with most people who will be affected by the benefit cap.","false","Biography information for Dawn Butler","Brent Central","Dawn Butler","10064"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418405","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-09-16","<p>Security of connected devices, the system they operate in and data is very important to consider in the Internet of Things. That is why security will be a theme throughout the government funded Internet of Things programme (IoTUK). We have included £10m for additional research to design in security, privacy and trust in IoT-related systems. In his report on the Internet of Things the Government Chief Scientist advised that security should be considered at the beginning and throughout the life cycle of Internet of Things applications. We have therefore made security a specific part of the competition scope for the large-scale demonstrator competitions.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-09-16T14:07:30.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418405/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418405/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418405/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-09-11","Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment he has made of the security of devices connected to the Internet of Things.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","10009"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418406","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-09-16","<p>Current superfast broadband coverage is over 83% of UK premises and the Government remains committed to providing 95% coverage to homes and businesses by December 2017. Coverage of superfast broadband in England is 84% according to Ofcom’s Communications Market Report published in August 2015. The report can be found at: <a href="http://stakeholders.ofcom.org.uk/binaries/research/cmr/cmr15/CMR_UK_2015.pdf" target="_blank">http://stakeholders.ofcom.org.uk/binaries/research/cmr/cmr15/CMR_UK_2015.pdf</a></p><p><br>The Government has invested £9.69 million in the Northumberland project which aims to provide superfast broadband coverage to over 46,000 homes and businesses in the county. By the end of the Northumberland project, anticipated by December 2016, over 91% of premises are expected to have access to superfast broadband. As of 30 June 2015, 40,193 premises had access to superfast broadband as a result of the project.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-09-16T14:11:17.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418406/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418406/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418406/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-09-11","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment he has made of the extent of superfast broadband coverage in (a) England and (b) Northumberland; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Anne-Marie Trevelyan","Berwick-upon-Tweed","Mrs Anne-Marie Trevelyan","10001"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418407","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-09-16","<p>The Government is considering whether to implement a broadband Universal Service Obligation (USO) as one of a range of options for reaching the final 5% of the UK population who do not have access to broadband in order to ensure that no one gets left behind. No decisions have been taken at this stage.</p><p> </p><p>Any broadband USO would have to comply with the European Universal Service Directive. The Directive does not specify a speed other than to indicate that it should be set at a level that is available to and used by the majority.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","10003","2015-09-16T14:13:17.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418407/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418407/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418407/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-09-11","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what plans he has to introduce a universal service obligation for superfast broadband coverage; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Anne-Marie Trevelyan","Berwick-upon-Tweed","Mrs Anne-Marie Trevelyan","10002"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418408","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-09-16","<p>The Government is considering whether to implement a broadband Universal Service Obligation (USO) as one of a range of options for reaching the final 5% of the UK population who do not have access to broadband in order to ensure that no one gets left behind. No decisions have been taken at this stage.</p><p> </p><p>Any broadband USO would have to comply with the European Universal Service Directive. The Directive does not specify a speed other than to indicate that it should be set at a level that is available to and used by the majority.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","10002","2015-09-16T14:13:17.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418408/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418408/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418408/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-09-11","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what plans he has to introduce a universal service obligation for broadband coverage; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Anne-Marie Trevelyan","Berwick-upon-Tweed","Mrs Anne-Marie Trevelyan","10003"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418409","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-09-17","<p>The Government is currently considering who should chair the Review, who should assist them and the finalised terms of reference and will make an announcement on commencement shortly. The Review will report its findings before 26 May 2016.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","9991","2015-09-17T14:42:58.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418409/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418409/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418409/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-09-11","Tickets: Sales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to the Consumer Rights Act 2015, what the (a) terms of reference, (b) composition of membership and (c) timescale is of the review into the secondary ticketing market.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","9990"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418410","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-09-17","<p>The Government is currently considering who should chair the Review, who should assist them and the finalised terms of reference and will make an announcement on commencement shortly. The Review will report its findings before 26 May 2016.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","9990","2015-09-17T14:42:59.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418410/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418410/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418410/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-09-11","Tickets: Sales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to the Consumer Rights Act 2015, when he expects the review into the secondary ticketing market to (a) commence and (b) report its findings.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","9991"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418411","Department for Education","false","2015-09-16","<p>The government recognises a key part of raising the standard of education for all children is to ensure they receive a good level of development in literacy and numeracy before they start school. The government has taken the following steps to ensure children are developing good early language skills before they reach primary school:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Early Years Foundation Stage sets the prime areas of learning which early years providers must follow. This includes a focus on communication and language. The Early Years Foundation Stage requires providers to understand the needs of every child and support them as necessary to make progress. The Early Years Foundation stage is available online at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/335504/EYFS_framework_from_1_September_2014__with_clarification_note.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/335504/EYFS_framework_from_1_September_2014__with_clarification_note.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The numeracy and literacy skills of staff working with our youngest children are key to supporting children’s progression. We have improved early years qualifications and encouraged high-quality entrants with good numeracy and literacy skills into the profession through setting clear criteria for level 3 training courses and introducing early years initial teacher training.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The government has invested over £50 million funding through the Early Years Pupil premium, an additional £5.3 million to sector organisations under the VCS grants and a one off grant of £5 million to teaching schools and their childcare provider partners to support staff development. Many of the projects funded through departmental grants are supporting staff to develop strong pedagogical approaches to language development and early literacy.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2015-09-16T14:12:34.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418411/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418411/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418411/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-09-11","Pre-school Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps her Department is taking to ensure that children develop good early language skills before they reach primary school.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","9973"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418412","Department for Education","false","2015-09-16","<p>All local authorities in England have a legal duty to ensure all three- and four-year-olds and the most disadvantaged two-year-olds are able to take up a funded early education place free of charge. Each eligible child is entitled to 570 hours of free early learning a year, equivalent to 15 hours a week of early education for 38 weeks per year. Settings delivering the funded early education entitlement are subject to inspection by Ofsted.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The early years pupil premium, which was introduced in April this year, provides nurseries and schools delivering the early education entitlement for three- and four-year-old children with an extra 53p an hour for each eligible child to help them raise the quality of their setting and so close the gap in school readiness between disadvantaged children and their peers. The Government has made £50 million available for the early years pupil premium in 2015-16.</p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2015-09-16T14:15:00.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418412/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418412/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418412/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-09-11","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps her Department is taking to ensure that disadvantaged children have access to good quality childcare.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","9974"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418413","Department for Education","false","2015-10-07","<p>Ministers have considered the latest evidence on the effective deployment and professional development of teaching assistants, together with a summary of the call for evidence and the draft teaching assistant standards submitted by the expert panel.</p><p> </p><p>In the light of this evidence, the Government believes that schools are best placed to decide how they use and deploy teaching assistants, and to set standards for the teaching assistants they employ. The Secretary of State has therefore decided not to publish the draft standards.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2015-10-07T09:40:42.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418413/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418413/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418413/answer","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418413/answer/previousversion/21854","Biography information for Nick Gibb","60","Education","Education","2015-09-11","Classroom Assistants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when she plans to publish the findings of her Department's review into the status and professionalism of teaching assistants announced in October 2014.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","10004"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418414","Department for Education","false","2015-09-21","<p>Only one school within the relevant areas is currently in special measures; the University of Chester Academy Northwich.</p><p> </p><p>The recent Ofsted monitoring inspections of 4 March 2015 and 10 June 2015, both found the school to be making reasonable progress towards the removal of special measures.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2015-09-21T09:21:30.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418414/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418414/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418414/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-09-11","Schools: Cheshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the current status is of schools placed in special measures in (a) Ellesmere Port and Neston constituency and (b) Cheshire West and Chester local authority area.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","10014"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418415","Department for Education","false","2015-09-21","<p>Education is a devolved power; as such, this reply concerns schools in England only.</p><p> </p><p>It is for schools to tailor their personal, social, health and economic education (PSHE) programme to reflect the needs of their pupils. We expect teachers to understand how best to create a safe environment for PSHE, so that pupils feel able to discuss and reflect on issues that are important to them. We have provided funding to the PSHE Association to work with schools to advise them in developing their own PSHE curriculum and improve the quality of teaching. This includes signposting schools to high-quality resources.</p><p> </p><p>Department for Education guidance on promoting the spiritual, moral, social and cultural development of pupils states that pupils must be encouraged to regard people of all faiths, races and cultures with respect and tolerance. The guidance for schools is found online at: <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/publications/promoting-fundamental-british-values-through-smsc" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/promoting-fundamental-british-values-through-smsc</a></p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2015-09-21T09:02:31.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418415/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418415/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418415/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-09-11","Personal, Social, Health and Economic Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps her Department is taking to ensure pupils are able to share information about their backgrounds and cultures as part of personal, social and health education.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","10019"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418416","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-24","<p>To date there has been no award of damages and litigation is ongoing.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-09-24T10:34:24.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418416/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418416/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418416/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-11","Department for Energy and Climate Change: Damages","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how much the Government has paid in damages in connection with the judgment in Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change v Friends of the Earth and Others, [2012], EWCA Civ 28 to date.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","10067"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418417","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-18","<p>Coal accounted for 40% of total UK electricity generation in 2012, falling to 29% in 2014. We expect the role of unabated coal generation to decline further as a result of deployment of low carbon alternatives, the cost of generation and the investment needed to meet new pollution abatement standards. The Department’s analysis (central scenario) shows that unabated coal is expected to account for around 1% of total UK generation by 2025.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government’s planning policy prevents the building of new coal power plants without carbon capture and storage.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><em>Source: DECC Updated energy and emissions projections 2014 <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/368021/Updated_energy_and_emissions_projections2014.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/368021/Updated_energy_and_emissions_projections2014.pdf</a></em></p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-09-18T13:09:32.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418417/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418417/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418417/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-11","Coal Fired Power Stations: Decommissioning","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, if she will publish a plan to phase out all unabated coal power.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","10068"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418418","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-21","<p>We will respond to the Committee on Climate Change’s Annual Progress Report by the 15<sup>th</sup> October. This will set out our response to each of the Committee’s recommendations.</p><p>In addition to this Government response, we will bring forward further proposals on how we plan to meet carbon budgets over the course of next year.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-09-21T12:28:34.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418418/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418418/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418418/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-11","Carbon Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, with reference to the findings of the Committee on Climate Change's 2014-15 Annual Report, what steps she is taking to achieve the necessary strengthening of policies identified to meet future carbon budgets.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","10069"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418419","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-10-12","<p>As stated in the impact assessment accompanying the consultation paper, the likely annual saving on average household electricity bills from the proposed early closure of the renewables obligation to solar PV at 5MW and below is £0.80 in 2020/21 on the medium deployment scenario, with a range from £0.50 to £1.20. These bill impact figures are in 2014 prices.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-10-12T13:50:31.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418419/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418419/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418419/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-11","Solar Power: Renewables Obligation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what estimate she has made of the likely annual saving on average household energy bills from the proposed early closure of the solar renewables obligation.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","10076"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418420","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-21","<p>The Government’s independent advisory body on climate change, the Committee on Climate Change (CCC), has considered the role of shale gas in previous reports about carbon budgets to 2027<sup><sup>[1]</sup></sup>; this included the second and third carbon budgets. They concluded that UK shale gas production can be consistent with meeting our carbon targets.</p><p>The Infrastructure Act 2015 places a new requirement on the Secretary of State to seek advice from the CCC on the likely impact of onshore oil and gas production (including shale gas) on meeting our carbon budgets and our 2050 80% emission reduction target. The first CCC report is due by 1 April 2016.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>[1] For an overview of the CCC work on shale gas please see also <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/documents/commons-committees/environmental-audit/EAC-Shale-gas-letter.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/documents/commons-committees/environmental-audit/EAC-Shale-gas-letter.pdf</a> .</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-09-21T12:26:29.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418420/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418420/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418420/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-11","Fracking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what assessment she has made of the effect of shale gas extraction on delivery of the (a) second and (b) third Carbon Budget.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","10074"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418421","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-22","<p>The Government is committed to meeting its targets for carbon emission reductions. The steps we are taking to achieve these targets include:</p><p>• helping consumers and businesses to save money on their energy bills;</p><p>• making buildings more energy efficient;</p><p>• helping consumers to take control of their energy use with smart meters, and</p><p>• decarbonising the power sector in the most cost effective way.</p><p>We will shortly be publishing our response on the Committee on Climate Change’s Annual Progress Report. This will outline in more detail the steps we are taking. In addition, we will bring forward further proposals on how we plan to meet our carbon targets over the course of next year.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-09-22T13:05:02.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418421/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418421/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418421/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-11","Carbon Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what steps she is taking to reduce carbon emissions by 50 per cent by 2025.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","10070"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418422","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-09-21","<p>The National Adaptation Programme report sets out over 370 actions that are being taken to address the risks identified in the UK Climate Change Risk Assessment, many of which impact on the well-being of UK citizens. The Government is committed to continue implementing the National Adaptation Programme, working across Government and with business, councils, civil society and academia.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2015-09-21T13:26:54.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418422/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418422/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418422/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-09-11","Climate Change","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, with reference to the Adaptation Sub-Committee Progress Report 2014, what steps she is taking to minimise the risks to the well-being of UK citizens identified in that report.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","10071"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418423","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-23","<p>Numbers on employment in the sector are not robust enough to show how many jobs are supported directly by the feed-in tariff (FIT) scheme, and for this reason it has not been possible to quantify with a high degree of confidence the impact of proposed changes on employment levels in the sector or the wider economy. We have asked a question in the FIT review consultation about the wider impact of changes.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-09-23T12:22:28.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418423/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418423/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418423/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-11","Solar Power: Feed-in Tariffs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, for what reasons the feed-in tariff review consultation did not consider the effect of changes to that tariff on levels of employment in the solar sector.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","10072"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418424","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-21","<p>Sellafield is the most hazardous site in Europe and contains the legacy ponds and silos – some of the most challenging decommissioning facilities. These have been deemed ‘intolerable’ by the Office of Nuclear Regulation, meaning that there can be no constraint on progress to remediate the hazards.</p><p>As part of its request for future funding as part of the Spending Review announced by HMT on 21 July, DECC’s return contains details of NDA’s estimates of expenditure in line with its existing plans.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-09-21T12:26:53.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418424/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418424/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418424/answer","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418424/answer/previousversion/21873","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-11","Sellafield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what her policy is on protecting high hazard areas of work at the Sellafield nuclear facility.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","10006"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418425","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-16","<p>The impact of any proposed Spending Review settlement for the Nuclear Decommissioning Authority on the wider economy, including skills, supply chain, SMEs and local economies, will be considered as part of the Spending Review. It will not be possible to conduct detailed analysis of impacts of any funding settlement on these matters, however, until the level of overall funding available is agreed and the Nuclear Decommissioning Authority and its contractors have had the opportunity to revise plans accordingly.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-09-16T13:10:35.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418425/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418425/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418425/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-11","Nuclear Installations: Decommissioning","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, if she will make an assessment of the effect on (a) skills, (b) the supply chain, (c) small and medium-sized enterprises and (d) local economies of potential reductions to funding of nuclear decommissioning.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","10007"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418426","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-22","<p>The Secretary of State keeps the costs of all DECC’s policies under review. Decisions on departmental budgets will be made as part of the current Spending Review, due to report in the Autumn.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-09-22T12:17:42.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418426/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418426/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418426/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-11","Nuclear Installations: Decommissioning","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, if she will make an assessment of the marginal annual cost to the public purse of delaying the UK's nuclear decommissioning programme.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","9992"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418427","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-21","<p>The Nuclear Decommissioning Authority (NDA) is in the process of submitting advice to DECC, which together with other sources of information and evidence, will enable DECC to consider options for the disposition of plutonium.</p><p>There are a number of options for disposing of plutonium that will be considered. There is variation in the generating potential of some of the options, so there is not one specific estimate of the generating potential of the UK’s plutonium inventory.</p><p>When the Government is confident that its preferred option for plutonium disposition could be implemented safely and securely, and in a way that is affordable, deliverable, and offers value for money, we will be in a position to proceed.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-09-21T12:29:18.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418427/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418427/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418427/answer","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418427/answer/previousversion/21872","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-11","Plutonium","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what the energy generating potential is of the UK's plutonium stockpile.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","9986"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418428","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-21","<p>The Nuclear Decommissioning Authority (NDA) are in the process of submitting advice to support DECC in its considerations. This, together with other sources of information and evidence, will enable DECC to consider options for the way forward. A decision is expected to be made by ministers on how to proceed during 2015/16. However, only when the Government is confident that its preferred option could be implemented safely and securely, in way that is affordable, deliverable, and offers value for money, will it be in a position to proceed.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-09-21T12:27:48.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418428/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418428/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418428/answer","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418428/answer/previousversion/21871","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-11","Plutonium","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, whether her Department plans to take a decision on the reuse options for managing plutonium stocks in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","9984"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418429","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-16","<p>As part of its request for future funding as part of the Spending Review announced by HM Treasury on 21 July, DECC’s departmental return contains details of the Nuclear Decommissioning Authority’s estimates of expenditure in the next Spending Review period. The potential impact on the supply chain of any settlement will be considered as part of the Spending Review.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-09-16T13:10:48.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418429/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418429/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418429/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-11","Nuclear Installations: Decommissioning","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what assessment she has made of the effect of reductions in funding to the nuclear decommissioning sector on the supply chain in that sector.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","9985"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418430","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-22","<p>The table below provides the number of domestic solar PV installations in the UK from 2010 to 2015 (data up to June for 2015). Data for Great Britain are for installations supported by the Feed in Tariff, designated as being for domestic use. For Northern Ireland, there is no breakdown of sector available, but all installations are less than 50 kW, and are all included here.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>GB</p></td><td><p>NI</p></td><td><p>UK</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>21,044</p></td><td><p>41</p></td><td><p>21,085</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>189,280</p></td><td><p>155</p></td><td><p>189,435</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>148,483</p></td><td><p>775</p></td><td><p>149,258</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>88,570</p></td><td><p>3,779</p></td><td><p>92,349</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>113,080</p></td><td><p>6,634</p></td><td><p>119,714</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>39,118</p></td><td><p>2,830</p></td><td><p>41,948</p></td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source:</p><p>GB data from the Central Feed-in Tariff Register, as at end of June 2015. A snap shot of cumulative installations as at the end of June 2015 is available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/sub-regional-feed-in-tariffs-confirmed-on-the-cfr-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/sub-regional-feed-in-tariffs-confirmed-on-the-cfr-statistics</a></p><p>Data for Northern Ireland from the Microgeneration Certification Scheme (and Renewables Obligation), also available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/solar-photovoltaics-deployment" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/solar-photovoltaics-deployment</a>.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-09-22T12:18:40.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418430/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418430/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418430/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-11","Solar Power: Renewables Obligation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how many domestic solar PV installations were made in the UK in each of the last five years for which records are available.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","10065"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418431","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-22","<p>Suppliers are required under the terms in their supply licence to ensure that differences in charges for different payment methods, which include the use of prepayment meters, reflect the costs they face to provide that payment method.</p><p>Across the market the prices of prepayment meter tariffs are now largely the same as those of standard variable tariffs and we are starting to see more improvements in the pre-payment meter market with the development of smart meters, for example E.ON is currently piloting a Smart Pay-As-You Go tariff for customers using a smart prepayment meter who then pay the same prices as the company’s direct debit customers and they expect to make the tariff more widely available to new and existing customers from next year.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-09-22T12:19:17.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418431/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418431/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418431/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-11","Energy: Meters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, if her Department will take steps to ensure that households which use prepayment meters do not pay higher charges than households which do not use such meters.","false","Biography information for Dawn Butler","Brent Central","Dawn Butler","10063"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418432","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-09-18","<p>The full version of the draft rural economy impacts paper was released on 1 July and is available on <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/draft-shale-gas-rural-economy-impacts-paper" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/draft-shale-gas-rural-economy-impacts-paper</a>. The draft paper was intended as a rapid review of existing literature; it is not analytically robust. Work on this paper was discontinued and we have no plans to update it.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2015-09-18T10:55:52.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418432/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418432/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418432/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-09-11","Fracking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will publish the final version of her Department's report, Shale Gas: Rural Economy Impacts.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","10066"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418433","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-09-17","<p>As this is a devolved matter this answer applies to England only.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Section 14(1) of the Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981 makes it illegal to release or allow to escape into the wild, any animal or plant which is not ordinarily resident in Great Britain and is not a regular visitor to Great Britain in a wild state, or is listed in Schedule 9 to the Act. Breaches of this legislation could lead to an unlimited fine and/or two years imprisonment on indictment.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In addition to the provisions of the Wildlife and Countryside Act, Orders made in accordance with the Import of Live Fish Act 1980 prohibit the unlicensed keeping or release of 47 species of non-native live fish and all non-native crayfish species.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2015-09-17T16:19:52.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418433/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418433/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418433/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-09-11","Non-native Species","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps her Department is taking to prevent the (a) escape and (b) illegal release of non-native wild animals from captivity.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","9958"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418434","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-09-16","<p>Food supply is part of our Critical National Infrastructure. Defra produces an annual Sector Resilience Plan which sets out the resilience of the sector to all relevant risks. A public summary of Sector Resilience Plans is published on GOV.UK.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The UK food industry has a highly effective and resilient supply chain owing to the size, geographic diversity and competitiveness. There is recognised dependency on other critical sectors such as fuel, energy, transport and communications however the food supply sector has demonstrated resilience in response to potentially disruptive challenges in recent years. Defra works closely with the food industry to ensure the continued resilience of food supply.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-09-16T12:04:57.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418434/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418434/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418434/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-09-11","Food Supply: Urban Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether the Government has carried out an assessment of the resilience of food supply chains to cities.","false","Biography information for Ms Gisela Stuart","Birmingham, Edgbaston","Ms Gisela Stuart","9968"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418435","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-16","<p>The Government welcomes the creation of the UN Guiding Principles on Business and Human Rights. In September 2013 the Government published an National Action Plan entitled “Good Business” setting out how we would implement the UN Guiding Principles and what action we would take to support the principles internationally including by encouraging other states to follow the principles and to publish their own national action plans where possible. The Government has provided financial support to the UN Working Group on the issue of human rights and transnational corporations and other business enterprises in their role to promote uptake of the Guiding Principles and develop guidance and best practice world-wide including for use in Malawi.</p>","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps",,"2015-09-16T14:42:30.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418435/answer","Biography information for Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418435/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418435/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-11","Malawi: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to support implementation of the UN Guiding Principles on Business and Human Rights by the government of Malawi.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","9961"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418436","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-18","<p>The Government of Yemen and the Saudi Arabian-led Coalition have made military gains in recent weeks against the Houthis and forces loyal to former President Saleh. We hope this will help build a base for the future return of the legitimate Yemeni Government. A political solution is the best way to achieve long-term stability in Yemen, and we remain fully and actively supportive of the UN’s efforts to bring an end to the conflict and resumption of an inclusive political process. The humanitarian situation remains dire, with 80 per cent of the population in need of assistance. The Department for International Development has allocated £55 million, through UN agencies and humanitarian Non-Governmental Organisations, to support Yemenis affected by the crisis. The risk of terrorist groups, such as al-Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula and ISIL-Yemen, exploiting the instability is also a major concern. We continue to work with regional and international partners to tackle the threat.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-09-18T11:29:31.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418436/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418436/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418436/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-11","Yemen: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the security situation in Yemen; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","9962"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418437","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-21","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer given by my hon. friend, the Member for Portsmouth North (Penny Mordaunt) on 16 July (PQ 7583).</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-09-21T13:39:11.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418437/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418437/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418437/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-11","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether UK-manufactured arms are being used in the conflict in Yemen; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","9963"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418438","Department for International Development","false","2015-09-17","<p>DFID provides humanitarian assistance which includes provision of support to UNHCR and other actors, such as NGOs, who are responsible for delivering assistance to refugees across the world. This includes in DRC, Somalia, South Sudan and other countries. We are closely monitoring the humanitarian situation in Libya, including the situation of refugees and internally displaced people.</p><p> </p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2015-09-17T15:36:01.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418438/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418438/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418438/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-09-11","Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps the Government is taking to support refugees from (a) Libya, (b) South Sudan, (c) Somalia, (d) Democratic Republic of Congo and (e) other countries.","false","Biography information for Dawn Butler","Brent Central","Dawn Butler","9964"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418439","Department for International Development","false","2015-09-16","<p>Details of Ministerial overseas travel is published quarterly and is available on the <a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank">gov.uk</a> website.</p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2015-09-16T13:50:13.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418439/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418439/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418439/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-09-11","UN Sustainable Development Summit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, which Ministers and how many officials will take part in the UK delegation at the UN Sustainable Development Summit in September 2015; and what estimate she has made of the cost of their attendance at that summit.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","9999"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418440","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-18","<p>We have not received any recent reports with regards to possible oppression of the Amhara people in Ethiopia. The UK Government takes seriously all allegations of human rights abuses. Whenever credible allegations of human rights infringements are brought to our attention we raise them with the relevant authorities.</p>","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps",,"2015-09-18T09:39:29.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418440/answer","Biography information for Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418440/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418440/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-11","Ethiopia: Ethnic Groups","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent reports he has received on oppression of the Amahara people in Ethiopia.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","10058"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418441","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-16","<p>As we have previously stated we do not provide combat training to the Burmese Army.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2015-09-16T13:10:35.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418441/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418441/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418441/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-11","Burma: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what information he holds on whether Burmese army soldiers who have received training from the UK Government are serving in conflicts in (a) Kachin and Shan states or (b) Kokang areas.","false","Biography information for Valerie  Vaz","Walsall South","Valerie Vaz","10077"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418442","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-21","<p>UN Security Council Resolution 1606 reaffirmed support for the Arusha Peace Agreement and began the process for establishing a truth commission and special chamber within Burundi’s court system to ensure reconciliation and bring to justice those responsible for crimes against humanity and war crimes. Progress by the Burundian government has been extremely slow with the Truth and Reconciliation Law only submitted to Parliament in December 2012 and the Truth and Reconciliation Commission appointed in December 2014. More recently, the Burundian government has refused to engage with the UN and has refused the appointment of a UN Special Envoy to Burundi. The UK Government continues to voice concerns over the delay given the links between impunity and instability in Burundi.</p>","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps",,"2015-09-21T11:13:14.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418442/answer","Biography information for Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418442/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418442/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-11","Burundi: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what reports he has received on progress made by the Burundian government on the commitments made in UN Security Council resolution 1606.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","10059"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418443","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-21","The Burundian government first submitted the Truth and Reconciliation Law to Parliament in December 2012 before announcing the appointment of the Truth and Reconciliation Commission on 3 December 2014. It has not reported further since then. We understand that opposition parties boycotted the process over the remit of the Commission, calling into question its ability to establish the truth and bring reconciliation. The UK Government believes that the Truth and Reconciliation Commission, guided by the Arusha Agreement signed in the aftermath of Burundi’s civil war, has an important role in ensuring long-term reconciliation. The illegitimate elections and continued violence show that the principles of inclusion set out in the Arusha Agreement are needed now more than ever and we continue to urge all in Burundi to uphold them.","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps",,"2015-09-21T11:14:51.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418443/answer","Biography information for Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418443/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418443/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-11","Burundi: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what reports he has received on progress by the Burundian government on establishing a truth commission.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","10060"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418444","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-16","<p>I refer the hon. member to my answer of 3 December 2014 (PQ <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2014-11-27/216319/" target="_blank">216319</a>).</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2015-09-16T13:15:31.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418444/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418444/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418444/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-11","Burma: Crimes against Humanity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will make an assessment of the implication for his policies of the Harvard Law School report entitled War Crimes and Crimes Against Humanity in Eastern Myanmar published in November 2014; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Valerie  Vaz","Walsall South","Valerie Vaz","10079"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418445","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-18","<p>The Council Decision of 29 March 1994, also known as the Ioannina Compromise, was superseded by the Treaty of Nice, and subsequently by the Treaty of Lisbon in 2007. From 2014, a new version of the Ioannina Compromise took effect. This allows a group of Member States short of a blocking minority to request a deferral of decisions they do not agree with, within a reasonable timeframe. The Government does not maintain a central record of when the provision has been invoked or for what reason.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2015-09-18T12:25:47.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418445/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418445/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418445/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-11","EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 3 July 2015 to Question 4126, how many times the procedure provided for in the Council Decision of 29 March 1994 have been invoked; what the concerns of the member states that invoked the procedure were in each such case; and how those concerns were met in the final decision taken in each such case.","false","Biography information for Mr David Nuttall","Bury North","Mr David Nuttall","10013"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418446","Department of Health","false","2015-09-17","<p>Information provided by the Health and Social Care Information Centre shows that during 2013/14 there were 159,626 referrals from optometrists to secondary care. It is not possible, however, to identify a diagnosis given the collection of this information is not mandatory.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-09-17T10:07:37.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418446/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418446/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418446/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-11","Eyesight: Testing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many people were diagnosed with (a) a brain tumour and (b) other conditions as a result of symptoms noticed during examinations by opticians in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","10017"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418447","Department of Health","false","2015-09-21","<p>Decisions regarding the appropriateness of a particular treatment, including statins, should be made by clinicians in partnership with patients. The individual circumstances of each patient should be taken into account, alongside their medical history, needs and preferences.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-09-21T10:04:02.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418447/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418447/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418447/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-11","Statins","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will take steps to ensure patients prescribed statins can make a choice on what type of statins they receive.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","10020"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418448","Department of Health","false","2015-09-21","<p>The Health and Social Care Information Centre collects this information on behalf of the Department and it is made publicly available at the following web addresses:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.hscic.gov.uk/catalogue/PUB00417/nhs-stop-smok-serv-eng-2010-2011-tab.xls" target="_blank">http://www.hscic.gov.uk/catalogue/PUB00417/nhs-stop-smok-serv-eng-2010-2011-tab.xls</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.hscic.gov.uk/catalogue/PUB07011/stat-stop-smok-eng-apr-11-mar-12-tab1.xls" target="_blank">http://www.hscic.gov.uk/catalogue/PUB07011/stat-stop-smok-eng-apr-11-mar-12-tab1.xls</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.hscic.gov.uk/catalogue/PUB12228/stat-stop-smok-serv-eng-apr-12-mar-13-tab1.xls" target="_blank">http://www.hscic.gov.uk/catalogue/PUB12228/stat-stop-smok-serv-eng-apr-12-mar-13-tab1.xls</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.hscic.gov.uk/catalogue/PUB14610/stat-stop-smok-serv-eng-apr-13-mar-14-tab.xlsx" target="_blank">http://www.hscic.gov.uk/catalogue/PUB14610/stat-stop-smok-serv-eng-apr-13-mar-14-tab.xlsx</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.hscic.gov.uk/catalogue/PUB18002/stat-stop-smok-serv-eng-annual-1415.xlsx" target="_blank">http://www.hscic.gov.uk/catalogue/PUB18002/stat-stop-smok-serv-eng-annual-1415.xlsx</a></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-09-21T10:05:51.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418448/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418448/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418448/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-11","Smoking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what information his Department holds on how many people of what age ranges gave up smoking in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","10021"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418449","Department of Health","false","2015-09-17","<p>The Department has no plans to commission a study on the specific risk of transmission of Alzheimer’s disease in dentistry. There is no evidence that Alzheimer's disease can be transmitted through any medical procedure. In dentistry, patients are protected from the risk of infection by either mandatory single use instruments, or where instruments are reused, by guidance on strict decontamination procedures as per the Health Technical Memorandum 01-05: Decontamination in primary care dental practices - 2013 edition.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-09-17T16:09:59.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418449/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418449/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418449/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-11","Alzheimer's Disease: Dental Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will commission a study to investigate potential links between dental treatment and Alzheimer's disease.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","10023"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418450","Department of Health","false","2015-09-16","<p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence assesses significant new drugs and treatments, including those for the treatment of dementia, through its technology appraisal programme. Technology appraisals are conducted in accordance with NICE’s <em>Guide to the methods of technology appraisal 2013</em> which is available at:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.nice.org.uk/article/pmg9/chapter/Foreword" target="_blank">www.nice.org.uk/article/pmg9/chapter/Foreword</a></p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-09-16T15:15:57.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418450/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418450/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418450/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-11","Dementia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what criteria NICE has set for new dementia treatments to be recommended for provision by the NHS.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","10022"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418451","Department of Health","false","2015-09-16","<p>No such assessment has been made. We remain committed to continuing to invest in the Cancer Drugs Fund which has so far benefitted over 72,000 people with cancer in England.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We understand that NHS England continues to work with manufacturers seeking to maintain drug and indication combinations within the Fund.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>NHS England has confirmed that patients who are already receiving a drug/indication which is to be removed from the Fund will continue to be treated with that drug until they and their clinicians consider it appropriate to discontinue treatment. In addition, drugs removed from the Fund will continue to be available via Individual Funding Requests if the individual patient meets clinical exceptionality criteria.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-09-16T15:22:40.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418451/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418451/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418451/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-11","Cancer: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the implications for his policies of the decision by NHS England announced on 4 September 2015 to remove (a) the pancreatic cancer drug Abraxane and (b) 22 other drugs and indications from the Cancer Drugs Fund list of approved drugs.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","10091"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418452","Department of Health","false","2015-09-16","<p>NHS England has advised that the mechanisms for appeal are as set out in Appendix G, section 11 of the Cancer Drugs Fund Standard Operating Procedures which are published on NHS England’s website at:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/cdf-sop-2015-16.pdf" target="_blank">www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/cdf-sop-2015-16.pdf</a></p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-09-16T15:23:43.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418452/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418452/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418452/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-11","Cancer: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what mechanisms there are for appeal against NHS England's decision announced on 4 September 2015 to remove (a) Abraxane and (b) 22 other drugs and indications from the Cancer Drugs Fund list of approved drugs; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","10092"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418453","Department of Health","false","2015-09-16","<p>Neither the Department nor NHS England has made any such assessment.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Advances in medical science means that new cancer medicines are emerging all the time and NHS England needs to regularly prioritise its national Cancer Drugs Fund (CDF) list so people can access these too. Decisions on which treatments are included on the list are made by the CDF expert clinical panel because it is right these decisions are clinically led.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-09-16T15:25:30.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418453/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418453/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418453/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-11","Cancer: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the effect on cancer clinical trials of NHS England's decision announced on 4 September 2015 to remove (a) Abraxane and (b) 22 other drugs and indications from the Cancer Drugs Fund list of approved drugs; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","10093"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418454","Department of Health","false","2015-09-21","<p>Information on patient outcomes of those diagnosed with Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome (EDS) in London and Greater Manchester is not held centrally by the Department. EDS falls within specialised services managed by NHS England.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The UK Strategy for Rare Diseases sets out the Government’s on-going commitment to ensuring that patients with rare diseases, including EDS, have access to high quality services. The Strategy is discussed regularly with health bodies including NHS England. The national specialised service for atypical or complex cases aims to reduce times to diagnosis and reduce the number of hospital appointments required to achieve a specific diagnosis.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Information about the average time from diagnosis to referral for specialist treatment is not available centrally. Patients suspected of having EDS may be assessed and diagnosed in a wide range of settings. These include United Kingdom regional clinical genetics clinics and various other secondary and tertiary speciality clinics.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","9987 ; 9989","2015-09-21T10:00:16.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418454/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418454/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418454/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-11","Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent discussions his Department has had with health bodies on ensuring timely treatment for sufferers of Ehlers-Danlos syndrome.","false","Biography information for Mr David Nuttall","Bury North","Mr David Nuttall","9988"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418455","Department of Health","false","2015-09-16","<p>The ProtecT randomised controlled trial is evaluating the effectiveness, cost-effectiveness and acceptability of active monitoring, radical 3D conformal radiotherapy and radical prostatectomy in men with clinically localised prostate cancer, identified through population-based PSA (Prostate Specific Antigen) testing.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>There have already been over 100 published outputs from ProtecT and these are listed on the National Institute for Health Research (NIHR) website:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>www.nets.nihr.ac.uk/projects/hta/962099</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The researchers plan to publish the primary and most secondary analyses during 2016 at major relevant conferences and in peer-reviewed journals. The primary outcome to be evaluated is definite or probable prostate cancer specific mortality at a median of 10 years following randomisation. A monograph covering these findings is expected to be published in the NIHR Journals Library in July 2017. Findings from longer term follow-up will be published at a later stage.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-09-16T15:17:51.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418455/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418455/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418455/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-11","Prostate Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when he expects the final results of the National Institute for Health Research's ProtecT trials for prostate cancer testing to be published; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","9996"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418456","Department of Health","false","2015-09-16","<p>The Department's National Institute for Health Research (NIHR) welcomes funding applications for research into any aspect of human health, including muscular dystrophies. These applications are subject to peer review and judged in open competition, with awards being made on the basis of the importance of the topic to patients and health and care services, value for money and scientific quality.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Research on novel approaches to treating neuromuscular disease including Duchenne muscular dystrophy is being carried out by the NIHR Biomedical Research Centre at Great Ormond Street Hospital for Children NHS Trust and the University College London Institute of Child Health.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The NIHR Health Technology Assessment programme is currently seeking to commission research on the effectiveness and cost-effectiveness of mechanical insufflation-exsufflation devices when compared to other methods of sputum clearance commonly used in children and young people with neuromuscular disease.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-09-16T15:27:44.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418456/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418456/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418456/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-11","Muscular Dystrophy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to promote research into muscular dystrophy conditions.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","9997"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418457","Department of Health","false","2015-09-21","<p>Information on patient outcomes of those diagnosed with Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome (EDS) in London and Greater Manchester is not held centrally by the Department. EDS falls within specialised services managed by NHS England.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The UK Strategy for Rare Diseases sets out the Government’s on-going commitment to ensuring that patients with rare diseases, including EDS, have access to high quality services. The Strategy is discussed regularly with health bodies including NHS England. The national specialised service for atypical or complex cases aims to reduce times to diagnosis and reduce the number of hospital appointments required to achieve a specific diagnosis.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Information about the average time from diagnosis to referral for specialist treatment is not available centrally. Patients suspected of having EDS may be assessed and diagnosed in a wide range of settings. These include United Kingdom regional clinical genetics clinics and various other secondary and tertiary speciality clinics.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","9987 ; 9988","2015-09-21T10:00:17.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418457/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418457/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418457/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-11","Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the average length of time is between the diagnosis of a patient with Ehlers-Danlos syndrome and referral for specialist treatment in (a) London and (b) Greater Manchester.","false","Biography information for Mr David Nuttall","Bury North","Mr David Nuttall","9989"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418458","Department of Health","false","2015-09-16","<p>The Government fully appreciates the impact that sight loss can have on a person’s life and the importance of information being available for those newly diagnosed with sight loss, including signposting patients to appropriate support and rehabilitation services.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Eye clinics and their staffing, including eye clinic liaison officers, are commissioned and funded by individual clinical commissioning groups on the basis of local assessments of need.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","9977","2015-09-16T12:01:58.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418458/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418458/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418458/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-11","Ophthalmic Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent assessment he has made of the effect of eye clinic liaison officers on improving patient health and social care; and what progress he has made on increasing the provision of such officers.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","9980"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418459","Department of Health","false","2015-09-16","<p>The Government fully appreciates the impact that sight loss can have on a person’s life and the importance of information being available for those newly diagnosed with sight loss, including signposting patients to appropriate support and rehabilitation services.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Eye clinics and their staffing, including eye clinic liaison officers, are commissioned and funded by individual clinical commissioning groups on the basis of local assessments of need.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","9980","2015-09-16T12:01:58.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418459/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418459/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418459/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-11","Ophthalmic Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what funding his Department provides for eye clinic liaison officers.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","9977"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418460","Department of Health","false","2015-09-16","<p>Evidence based advice on the care of women with multiple pregnancies is set out in the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE ) Clinical Guidelines ‘Multiple Pregnancies – The management of twin and triplet pregnancies in the antenatal period’. In line with these guidelines, we would expect clinical care for women with twin and triplet pregnancies to be provided by a nominated multidisciplinary team consisting of a core team, including named specialist obstetricians, who have experience and knowledge of managing twin and triplet pregnancies. The Department has not undertaken an assessment of the effectiveness of the implementation of the NICE guidelines.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Local maternity care providers are responsible for determining how best to deliver services for women with multiple pregnancies in their area. In doing so we would expect them to give due regard to NICE guidelines.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>NHS England has asked Baroness Julia Cumberlege to lead a major review of maternity services to modernise care for women and babies across the country, as first set out in NHS England’s Five Year Forward View. The independent review group is assessing current maternity care provision, considering the evidence on different models of care and will make recommendations on how services should be developed to meet the changing needs of women and babies. The group met for the first time on 23 April and it plans to report by the end of the year. More information is available at:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.england.nhs.uk/2015/05/29/julia-cumberlege-2/" target="_blank">http://www.england.nhs.uk/2015/05/29/julia-cumberlege-2/</a></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2015-09-16T15:29:19.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418460/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418460/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418460/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-11","Multiple Births","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent assessment he has made of the (a) extent and (b) effectiveness of sharing of best practice of implementation of guidance on multiple pregnancies between NHS hospital trusts.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","9978"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418461","Department of Health","false","2015-09-21","<p>Information on patient outcomes of those diagnosed with Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome (EDS) in London and Greater Manchester is not held centrally by the Department. EDS falls within specialised services managed by NHS England.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The UK Strategy for Rare Diseases sets out the Government’s on-going commitment to ensuring that patients with rare diseases, including EDS, have access to high quality services. The Strategy is discussed regularly with health bodies including NHS England. The national specialised service for atypical or complex cases aims to reduce times to diagnosis and reduce the number of hospital appointments required to achieve a specific diagnosis.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Information about the average time from diagnosis to referral for specialist treatment is not available centrally. Patients suspected of having EDS may be assessed and diagnosed in a wide range of settings. These include United Kingdom regional clinical genetics clinics and various other secondary and tertiary speciality clinics.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","9988 ; 9989","2015-09-21T10:00:13.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418461/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418461/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418461/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-11","Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent assessment he has made of patient outcomes of those diagnosed with Ehlers-Danlos syndrome in (a) London and (b) Greater Manchester.","false","Biography information for Mr David Nuttall","Bury North","Mr David Nuttall","9987"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418462","Department of Health","false","2015-09-16","<p>No such assessment has been made, however we know that there are links between mental ill health and social factors like isolation and family breakdown and that men in certain age-groups are more likely to present with suicidal behaviour. Suicide continues to be more than three times as common in males than in females, 13.8 per 100,000 for males in 2011-13, compared to 4.0 for females.</p><p> </p><p><em> </em></p><p> </p><p><em>Preventing suicide in England: A cross-government outcomes strategy to save lives</em>, published in 2012, identified a number of high risk groups who are priorities for prevention young and middle-aged men. The strategy recognises that factors associated with suicide in men include family and relationship problems including marital breakup and social isolation. The strategy recognises that those who work with men in different settings, especially primary care, need to be particularly alert to the signs of suicidal behaviour.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>A review by the Samaritans, <em>Men Suicide and Society</em>, published in 2012, also highlighted that middle-aged men in certain socioeconomic groups are at particularly high risk of suicide. It pointed to evidence that suicidal behaviour results from the interaction of complex factors, including a lack of close social and family relationships, personal crises such as divorce, as well as a general ‘dip’ in subjective wellbeing among people in their mid-years, compared to both younger and older people. The report also found that relationship breakdown is more likely to lead men, rather than women, to suicide and was published in February 2015.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government’s first annual report on the suicide prevention strategy was published on 17 January 2014. It highlighted a new agreement designed to promote greater sharing of information with friends and family of people at risk of suicide. The second annual report into suicide prevention was written for people working in local services.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In January 2015, this Government called for every part of the National Health Service to commit to a 'zero suicide' ambition to dramatically reduce suicides. This goes beyond health service boundaries into the whole community, bringing in the police, education, housing, debt support services and so on.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-09-16T12:07:20.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418462/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418462/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418462/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-11","Suicide: Males","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the effect of family separation on male suicide rates.","false","Biography information for Mr Nicholas Brown","Newcastle upon Tyne East","Mr Nicholas Brown","9993"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418463","Department of Health","false","2015-09-16","<p>NHS England works in partnership with local commissioners and providers to ensure people with long-term conditions, such as hidradenitis suppurativa (HS), are supported to live healthily and independently and are empowered to take better control over the care they receive.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The majority of patients with HS can be managed through routine access to primary and secondary care, including dermatology clinics, which is responsibility of the local National Health Service commissioners. Treatment and management of the condition involves antibiotics, antiseptic washes and immunosuppressive treatments such as steroids or ciclosporin, which a general practitioner may prescribe.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>For those patients with the more serious forms of HS, referral to a specialised dermatology service may be appropriate. NHS England commissions services for people with rare and complex skin conditions, including HS, and has set out what providers must have in place in order to offer specialist dermatology care. This supports equity of access to a high quality service for patients wherever they live. These services may provide more intensive therapies with the involvement of a range of health and care professionals, subject to a patient’s needs. More information can be found by viewing the specialised dermatology service specification at the following link:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/a12-spec-dermatology.pdf" target="_blank">www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/a12-spec-dermatology.pdf</a></p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","10011","2015-09-16T11:46:53.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418463/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418463/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418463/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-11","Hidradenitis Suppurativa","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps NHS England takes to assess the health and social care needs of patients with hidradenitis suppurativa; and what assessment he has made of the ability of the NHS to deliver efficient diagnosis and access to specialist care for such patients.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","10010"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418464","Department of Health","false","2015-09-16","<p>NHS England works in partnership with local commissioners and providers to ensure people with long-term conditions, such as hidradenitis suppurativa (HS), are supported to live healthily and independently and are empowered to take better control over the care they receive.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The majority of patients with HS can be managed through routine access to primary and secondary care, including dermatology clinics, which is responsibility of the local National Health Service commissioners. Treatment and management of the condition involves antibiotics, antiseptic washes and immunosuppressive treatments such as steroids or ciclosporin, which a general practitioner may prescribe.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>For those patients with the more serious forms of HS, referral to a specialised dermatology service may be appropriate. NHS England commissions services for people with rare and complex skin conditions, including HS, and has set out what providers must have in place in order to offer specialist dermatology care. This supports equity of access to a high quality service for patients wherever they live. These services may provide more intensive therapies with the involvement of a range of health and care professionals, subject to a patient’s needs. More information can be found by viewing the specialised dermatology service specification at the following link:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/a12-spec-dermatology.pdf" target="_blank">www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/a12-spec-dermatology.pdf</a></p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","10010","2015-09-16T11:46:53.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418464/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418464/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418464/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-11","Hidradenitis Suppurativa","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what progress has been made by NHS England on the production of a commissioning policy for treatments associated with hidradenitis suppurativa; what the proposed scope of that policy is; and when he expects that policy to have been fully developed.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","10011"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418465","Department of Health","false","2015-09-21","<p>There is no plan to launch a Royal Commission into the future of the National Health Service. The Government remains committed to the principles of the NHS, enshrined in the NHS Constitution and in working with the NHS in implementing its own plan for the future of the NHS – the Five Year Forward View.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-09-21T12:53:10.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418465/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418465/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418465/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-11","NHS","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will bring forward proposals for an independent Royal Commission on the future of the NHS.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","9970"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418466","Home Office","false","2015-09-21","<p>In the last three years the UK has provided over 1,000 working days to support missions coordinated by the European Asylum Support Office (EASO) to other Member States under pressure. This is more than any other EU Member State. In addition, we continue to fund via the UNHCR asylum expertise to the Greek asylum system and support a programme of assisted voluntary return of illegal migrants.</p><p>We also support the European Commission’s proposals for 'Hot Spot' screening centres. These centres will help ensure that migrants are registered and fingerprinted at pressure points on the EU external border and that refugees are identified and protected quickly, while those with no need of protection can be returned immediately. We are discussing with EASO and Frontex how best we can contribute.</p><p>We have created a multi-agency 90-strong team from the National Crime Agency (NCA), Border Force, Immigration Enforcement and the CPS to fight the criminal gangs that are exploiting vulnerable people and are working closely with Europol to strengthen its operation to tackle organised crime groups involved in smuggling people across sea and land routes. We are focusing on tracking vessels in the Mediterranean and bringing together intelligence from EU and Europol partners to target these criminals.</p><p>We continue to support Frontex operations in the Mediterranean by providing debriefing and nationality screening experts to Operations Triton and Poseidon. The UK has an outstanding offer of additional debriefing and nationality screening experts which was made to Frontex during August. We are currently awaiting directions from Frontex as to where this resource may best be utilised.</p><p>The UK is excluded from the Frontex Regulation on Schengen-building grounds. Therefore our officers participate in Frontex joint operations and other activities with the agreement of the Management Board on a case-by-case basis in an observational/advisory role.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2015-09-21T15:15:48.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418466/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418466/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418466/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-11","Refugees: EU Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what practical support EU member states, which have recently received the highest numbers of refugees, have requested from the UK; and what such support the Government has provided.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","9971"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418467","Home Office","false","2015-09-18","<p>Following advice from the independent Migration Advisory Committee, the Government introduced an annual limit on Tier 2, the skilled work route, in 2011. In 2012 the Government announced that from 6 April 2016 Tier 2 migrants who apply for settlement in the UK will be required to meet a minimum annual salary requirement of £35,000.</p><p>The Home Office published full impact assessments on these changes when the rules were laid before Parliament. The impact assessments are available on the gov.uk website as follows:</p><p>Annual limit: https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/migration-permanent-limit-tier-1-and-tier-2-impact-assessment</p><p>Settlement: https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/changes-affecting-employment-related-settlement-tier-5-and-overseas-domestic-workers</p><p>Under the annual limit, NHS trusts have been given more than 1,400 Tier 2 certificates of sponsorship for nurses since April this year but over 600 of the places allocated to them in April and May this year have been returned unused.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","9967","2015-09-18T15:49:00.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418467/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418467/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418467/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-11","Nurses: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the effect of recent changes to immigration rules on nurse staffing levels in the independent and private sectors.","false","Biography information for Mr Mark Williams","Ceredigion","Mr Mark Williams","9966"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418468","Home Office","false","2015-09-18","<p>Following advice from the independent Migration Advisory Committee, the Government introduced an annual limit on Tier 2, the skilled work route, in 2011. In 2012 the Government announced that from 6 April 2016 Tier 2 migrants who apply for settlement in the UK will be required to meet a minimum annual salary requirement of £35,000.</p><p>The Home Office published full impact assessments on these changes when the rules were laid before Parliament. The impact assessments are available on the gov.uk website as follows:</p><p>Annual limit: https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/migration-permanent-limit-tier-1-and-tier-2-impact-assessment</p><p>Settlement: https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/changes-affecting-employment-related-settlement-tier-5-and-overseas-domestic-workers</p><p>Under the annual limit, NHS trusts have been given more than 1,400 Tier 2 certificates of sponsorship for nurses since April this year but over 600 of the places allocated to them in April and May this year have been returned unused.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","9966","2015-09-18T15:49:00.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418468/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418468/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418468/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-11","Nurses: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of recent changes to immigration rules on retention and recruitment of nurses.","false","Biography information for Mr Mark Williams","Ceredigion","Mr Mark Williams","9967"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418469","Home Office","false","2015-09-17","<p>The Proceeds of Crime Act 2002 permits an application for a restraint order to be made to “freeze” the property of an alleged offender and has the effect of freezing realisable property that may be liable to a later confiscation order. The Act defines realisable property as any free property held by the defendant including any intangible or incorporeal property. The intellectual property rights in a domain name could fall within this definition and so a restraint order would be available. A company is a separate legal entity to its shareholders and directors and so a restraint order against realisable property held by a company would only be available where the alleged offender was that company. The terms of the restraint order prevent the alleged offender from dealing with their realisable property. Whilst property is under restraint, the judge may, depending on the circumstances of the case, exempt property which is required for legitimate business purposes to enable a person to carry on any trade, profession or occupation, for example, to enable continued use of a domain name.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-09-17T11:27:11.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418469/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418469/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418469/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-11","Company Investigations: Freezing of Assets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether the scope of police powers to freeze company assets encompasses a company domain name; what provisions exists for such a domain name to be renewed if it was frozen during a police investigation; who is permitted to renew such a name where a company under investigation has no access to its assets; and what recourse a company has to regain its domain name if it was lost during the course of a police investigation.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","9975"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418470","Cabinet Office","false","2015-09-15","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2015-09-15T16:18:11.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418470/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418470/answer","PQ10012.pdf","PQ10012.pdf","UKSA Letter to Member - Refugee Citizenships","UKSA Letter to Member - Refugee Citizenships","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418470/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-09-11","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what estimate he has made of the number of non-UK EU citizens residing in the UK who were previously refugees granted citizenship in another EU member state in the most recent period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Mr David Nuttall","Bury North","Mr David Nuttall","10012"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418471","Home Office","false","2015-09-16","<p>The Proceeds of Crime Act 2002 permits an application for a restraint order to be made to “freeze” assets of an alleged offender, which includes a company, if there is reasonable cause to suspect that an offender has benefitted from their criminal conduct. A restraint order has the effect of freezing property that may be liable to confiscation following a trial and the subsequent making of a confiscation order. There is no legal requirement for a police force to freeze the assets of a company they are investigating, although it is good practice to do so in cases in which assets need to be preserved for confiscation at a later date. A restraint order may be made by a Crown Court if any of the following conditions are satisfied:</p><p>(1) A criminal investigation has been started in England and Wales and there is reasonable grounds to suspect that the alleged offender has benefitted from criminal conduct</p><p>(2) Proceedings for an offence have been commenced in England and Wales and not concluded and there is reasonable grounds to believe that an alleged offender has benefitted from criminal conduct.</p><p>In addition to the statutory conditions, there must be a real risk that the assets will be dissipated.</p><p>A restraint order can be varied or discharged upon application by a person affected by the order. The Proceeds of Crime Act also provides that the court is required to discharge any restraint order at the conclusion of proceedings. If an order is made under condition (1) above, the court is also required to monitor progress with the investigation, and if a decision to charge is not made within a reasonable time, the court may discharge the restraint order.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-09-16T12:20:37.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418471/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418471/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418471/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-11","Company Investigations: Freezing of Assets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether Sussex Police are required to freeze the assets of a company they are investigating; on what grounds police may freeze the assets of a company they are investigating; and at what point such assets may be unfrozen if police bail has expired and no charges have been brought.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","9976"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418472","Home Office","false","2015-09-16","<p>It is Home Office policy not to comment on whether an individual is, or is not, excluded from the UK unless the person concerned has already put this information into the public domain themselves, or if the information is already in the public domain.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-09-16T12:19:02.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418472/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418472/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418472/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-11","Burma: Exclusion Orders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether the Burmese Home Affairs Minister, Lt. Gen. Ko Ko, is excluded from entering the UK.","false","Biography information for Valerie  Vaz","Walsall South","Valerie Vaz","10078"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418473","Home Office","false","2015-09-17","<p>The Criminal Injuries Compensation Authority cannot provide data on the compensation it has awarded to victims of a particular crime type. This is because it awards compensation in line with the Criminal Injuries Compensation Scheme tariff of injuries rather than the type of incident that led to those injuries.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-09-17T11:30:02.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418473/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418473/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418473/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-11","Criminal Injuries Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many victims of (a) human trafficking for non-sexual exploitation and (b) forced labour, slavery and servitude have been awarded compensation through the Criminal Injuries Compensation Authority since 2014.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","10048"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418474","Home Office","false","2015-09-16","<p>Vehicle crime is at its lowest level since 1995 and theft of vehicles has fallen over a third since 2010 according to the Independent Crime Survey for England and Wales. We are not complacent, however, and we remain alert to changes in trends. We are working very closely with the police and industry on the issue of electronic vehicle theft to ensure that, together, we have up to date responses in place.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-09-16T17:00:58.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418474/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418474/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418474/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-11","Motor Vehicles: Theft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if her Department will take steps to reduce the number of thefts of hi-tech vehicles.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","10018"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418475","Home Office","false","2015-09-18","<p>The Gangmasters Licensing Authority (GLA) have established Licensing Standards against which applicants and existing licence holders are assessed. They are all legal requirements to protect workers from poor treatment and exploitation and set out the conditions that must be met to obtain and hold a GLA licence.</p><p>The Standards are published on the GLA website at:-</p><p>http://www.gla.gov.uk/Guidance/Information-on-Licensing/Licencing-Standards/. They include treatment of workers, accommodation and working conditions among others. Any non-compliance with the Standards is treated very seriously and would bear on the risk a licence holder poses. In addition, the GLA receives intelligence from partner agencies, such as police forces, about businesses which would also be taken into account in assessing risk. The GLA can inspect businesses where there are concerns.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-09-18T10:43:38.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418475/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418475/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418475/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-11","Gangmasters Licensing Authority","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what criteria are used by the Gangmasters Licensing Authority to establish whether a licence holder is high risk.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","10044"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418476","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-18","<p>The Department published an assessment of the impact of the Regulations on employers and workers in December 2014. This can be found at this link</p><p><a href="http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2014/3322/impacts" target="_blank">http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2014/3322/impacts</a></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-09-18T10:13:47.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418476/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418476/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418476/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-11","Slavery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the effects of the Deduction From Wages (Limitation) Regulations 2014 on employment law claims made by victims of modern slavery.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","10045"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418477","Home Office","false","2015-09-18","<p>An employer is excused from liability for a civil penalty if they show that they have complied with the prescribed right to work checks. There are no categories of statutory excuse.</p><p>The civil penalty regime and right to work checks are set out in the Immigration, Asylum and Nationality Act 2006, secondary legislation and published statutory codes of practice and guidance.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-09-18T15:49:34.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418477/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418477/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418477/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-11","Undocumented Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 21 July 2015 to Question 6173, what the categories of statutory excuses established by employers are which result in no action notices or notification of no liability.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","10041"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418478","Home Office","false","2015-09-18","<p>There are no changes to staffing levels currently planned for the next 12 months. We are developing proposals to improve labour market enforcement involving the Gangmasters Licensing Authority and will consult on those in due course.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-09-18T15:48:17.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418478/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418478/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418478/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-11","Gangmasters Licensing Authority: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what changes are planned to the level of staffing in the Gangmasters Licensing Authority in the next 12 months.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","10042"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418479","Home Office","false","2015-09-18","<p>The Government presented the Protocol to the Forced Labour Convention to Parliament on 6 February 2015, where it remained for 21 sitting days to allow scrutiny by both Houses. The UK is already compliant with the measures set out in the protocol and the Government will seek to ratify it shortly.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-09-18T10:40:33.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418479/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418479/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418479/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-11","Convention concerning Forced or Compulsory Labour","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 16 July 2015 to Question 6159, if she will establish a timeframe for ratification of the Protocol to the 2014 Forced Labour Convention.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","10040"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418480","Home Office","false","2015-10-21","<p>The total number of staff involved in frontline inspection activity is 55. This includes staff who carry out physical inspections for compliance purposes, those who undertake enforcement activity, and those who provide logistical and intelligence gathering support.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-10-21T15:59:12.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418480/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418480/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418480/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-11","Gangmasters Licensing Authority: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many staff of the Gangmasters Licensing Authority are dedicated to frontline inspection activity.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","10043"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418481","Home Office","false","2015-09-16","<p>The Licensing Act 2003 gives licensing authorities the power to make decisions regarding licensed opening hours.</p><p>Decisions are based on individual consideration of each premises application, as appropriate for the promotion of the licensing objectives and in line with the licensing authority’s statement of licensing policy.</p><p>The Government has no plans to change this aspect of the alcohol licensing regime.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-09-16T12:21:08.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418481/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418481/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418481/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-11","Off-licences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, between what hours alcohol is not permitted to be sold from off-licences; and what plans to change such restrictions the Government has.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","10061"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418482","Department for International Development","false","2015-09-18","<p>DFID is committed to supporting Climate Smart Development which tackles climate change and reduces poverty in developing countries. Our programmes aim to increase the ability of poor people to cope with the impacts of climate-related shocks, including droughts, floods and storms, and to build their resilience to future changes in climate. The International Climate Fund (ICF) is the UK Government’s vehicle for delivering climate finance assistance and other forms of support, such as technical assistance. Through the ICF the UK government is providing £3.87bn in support between 2011/12 and 2015/16.</p>","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps",,"2015-09-18T10:53:10.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418482/answer","Biography information for Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418482/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418482/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-09-11","Developing Countries: Climate Change","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what (a) financial and (b) other support her Department is providing to the least developed countries to tackle climate change and its effects.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","10075"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418483","Department for International Development","false","2015-09-18","<p>DFID is committed to supporting Climate Smart Development which tackles climate change and reduces poverty. This approach focuses on building the resilience of people in developing countries to the impacts of climate change, supporting economic development through low carbon growth, and promoting good governance of natural resources. A key part of this approach is to ensure that DFID programmes help address climate change, including reducing emissions.</p>","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps",,"2015-09-18T10:54:48.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418483/answer","Biography information for Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418483/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418483/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-09-11","Overseas Aid: Greenhouse Gas Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps she is taking to ensure funding disbursed by her Department does not contribute to increased greenhouse gas emissions.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","10073"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418484","Department for International Development","false","2015-09-16","<p>DFID Burma’s funding for education through religious organisations has the key policy objective of increasing the number and proportion of children who complete a quality basic education. The programme is delivered through the Myanmar Education Consortium which works with a range of Non-Governmental Organisations, including faith-based organisations, provided that i) the education services are available to members of different religious communities, ii) the project activities supported do not aim to proselytize or explicitly promote a particular religion, iii) where possible promote inter-communal peace and conflict resolution, and iv) do not engage in any action that could promote inter-communal tensions.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2015-09-16T13:33:50.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418484/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418484/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418484/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-09-11","Burma: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what her Department's policy is on the provision of funding for education through religious organisations in Burma.","false","Biography information for Valerie  Vaz","Walsall South","Valerie Vaz","10080"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418485","Department for International Development","false","2015-09-16","<p>UK Ministers and the Secretary of State for International Development frequently discuss Syrian refugees with Arab League members and other governments from the Middle East. These discussions include all aspects of the refugees including resettlement and raising the funding necessary to meet the needs of Syrians still in Syria and those seeking refuge in neighbouring countries.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2015-09-16T13:36:25.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418485/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418485/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418485/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-09-11","Middle East: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if she will hold discussions with the Arab League and other governments in the Middle East on the number of refugees each such country plans to resettle.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","9995"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418486","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-09-21","<p /> <p>The Ministry of Justice does not collect information centrally on Litigants in Person in family court cases. It publishes quarterly figures on the number of disposals and the average time taken for their disposal by case type and by the legal representation of the parties.</p><p>The latest figures up to quarter 1 (January to March) 2015 can be found here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/family-court-statistics-quarterly-january-to-march-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/family-court-statistics-quarterly-january-to-march-2015</a>.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2015-09-21T14:11:25.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418486/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418486/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418486/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-09-11","Family Proceedings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what estimate he has made of the number of litigants in person in the family justice system in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","9956"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418487","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-09-16","<p /> <p>Staff employed at Rainsbrook STC at the time of the transfer will transfer to the new provider, MTC Novo, under TUPE Regulations, unless they choose not to.</p><p>It is not appropriate to speculate or prejudge staffing requirements or the outcome of the transfer process.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2015-09-16T13:46:42.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418487/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418487/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418487/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-09-11","Secure Training Centres: Redundancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether any staff redundancies are planned as a result of the allocation of new contracts at Rainsbrook and Medway secure training centres.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","10090"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418488","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-11-13","<p>Secure Training Centres (STCs) play an important role in helping young people to reform and turn their lives around. They typically cater for younger offenders with multiple or complex needs, and therefore have smaller units and higher staff ratios than some other youth establishments.</p><p>The estimated average annual cost per place over the 5 year contract period at Rainsbrook STC is £136k and at Medway STC it is £138k. These figures are based on the bid price, uplifted in line with forecasted inflation.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2015-11-13T14:47:08.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418488/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418488/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418488/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-09-11","Secure Training Centres: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what estimate he has made of the annual cost per place of (a) MTCnovo's contract to run Rainsbrook Secure Training Centre and (b) G4S Care and Justice Services contract to run Medway Secure Training Centre.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","10089"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418489","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-10-08","<p>Tenders to run Rainsbrook and Medway secure training centres were evaluated using a standard approach balancing quality and price. This included criteria relating to the quality of proposals for custodial services, property and facilities management, mobilisation and ICT.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2015-10-08T15:08:44.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418489/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418489/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418489/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-09-11","Secure Training Centres: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what criteria were used to award the contracts for running Rainsbrook and Medway secure training centres.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","10087"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418490","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-09-16","<p /> <p>The award date was indicative only and it is not unusual for this to change. This has been a large and complex procurement that has involved extensive dialogue with all five bidders and a stringent governance process.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2015-09-16T13:27:00.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418490/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418490/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418490/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-09-11","Secure Training Centres: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, why his Department did not award new five year contracts to run Rainsbrook and Medway secure training centres at the time originally scheduled.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","10088"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418491","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-09-21","<p /> <p>The procurement process for the operation of both Rainsbrook STC and Medway STC was undertaken objectively and transparently against the published evaluation criteria and in accordance with the published evaluation booklet that was signed up to by bidders as part of the procurement process.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2015-09-21T12:01:51.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418491/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418491/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418491/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-09-11","Rainsbrook Secure Training Centre","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what consideration was given to the findings of the inspection of Rainsbrook Secure Training Centre, published on 20 May 2015, in making the decision to award new contracts for the running of that centre.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","10057"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418492","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-09-22","<p>The Youth Justice Board intends to extend the contract with G4S at Rainsbrook Secure Training Centre for five months to ensure a smooth transfer to the new provider.<br> <br> During this period MTCnovo's mobilisation team will work on site with G4S to manage the transfer. <br> <br> YJB staff will also work on site with both MTCnovo and G4S to monitor the progress of mobilisation and transformation and to ensure young people are accommodated in a safe and stable environment throughout.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2015-09-22T09:32:38.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418492/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418492/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418492/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-09-11","Rainsbrook Secure Training Centre","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the timescales and processes are for the handover of Rainsbrook Secure Training Centre from G4S Care and Justice Services to MTCnovo","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","10086"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418493","Department for International Development","false","2015-09-16","<p>I intend to represent Her Majesty’s Government at the Global Leader’s meeting on Gender Equality and Women’s Empowerment on 27 September 2015.</p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2015-09-16T13:34:48.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418493/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418493/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418493/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-09-11","Gender: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if the Prime Minister will attend the Global Leader's meeting on Gender Equality and Women's Empowerment on 27 September 2015.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","9972"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418494","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-16","<p>The core scheme of Gospel Oak to Barking electrification has now completed GRIP 3. Network Rail is working with stakeholders to deliver completion of works (GRIP 7) by June 2017 for this section. GRIP 3 work on the electrification of the linking lines from the core scheme to the docks and to the other London electrified lines is underway but has yet to complete.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-09-16T14:45:05.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418494/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418494/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418494/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-11","Gospel Oak-Barking Railway Line: Electrification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what stage of the guide to railway investment projects process has the Barking to Gospel Oak electrification project reached; and whether a date has been agreed with stakeholders for reaching stage seven.","false","Biography information for Stella Creasy","Walthamstow","Stella Creasy","9959"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418495","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-09-16","<p /> <p>There has been a long term decrease in the number of cases of causing death by careless and dangerous driving and, generally, an increase in the average custodial sentence lengths.</p><p>Information on the length of custodial sentences imposed for offenders convicted of causing death by careless and dangerous driving can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/428943/cjs-outcomes-by-offence-data-tool.xls" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/428943/cjs-outcomes-by-offence-data-tool.xls</a>.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2015-09-16T15:02:50.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418495/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418495/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418495/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-09-11","Dangerous Driving: Sentencing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what recent assessment he has made of trends in the length of sentences handed down to people who have been convicted of causing death by (a) careless and (b) dangerous driving; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","9979"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418496","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-16","<p>We have not estimated the cost of constructing a link road to Leeds Bradford International Airport as this would be a local road and the relevant local authority would be responsible for developing a scheme proposal. The Government sponsored study into improving connectivity to Leeds Bradford International Airport used an estimate provided by Leeds City Council of £38m in 2012 prices.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Aviation Policy Framework published in March 2013 makes clear that developers should pay the costs of upgrading transport links where there is a need to cope with increased passenger numbers, but that a public funding contribution will be considered if the scheme has a wider range of beneficiaries. The relevant local authorities would therefore be responsible for assembling a funding package for a link road, in partnership with developers and other local stakeholders. Local Growth Funding could be used to provide a public sector contribution, and the West Yorkshire Combined Authority is being provided with a contribution of up to £781m towards the West Yorkshire Plus Transport Fund between 2015/15 and 2034/35. The Fund has been set up to deliver transport improvements across West Yorkshire and York.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-09-16T11:27:13.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418496/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418496/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418496/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-11","Regional Airports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 21 July to Question 6770, what estimate he has made of the cost of a new link road; and from what sources funding for that link road will be provided.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","10005"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418497","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-21","<p>(a) The initial industry plan (IIP) of September 2011 for England and Wales, which set out a range of options for investment in the railway in Control Period 5, included proposals for funding of up to an additional £4.9 billion beyond that already committed. The separate IIP for Scotland included proposals for up to an additional £699 million.</p><p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p>(b) Network Rail’s Strategic Business Plan (SBC) for England and Wales, published in January 2013, included a total of £10.041 billion and the SBC for Scotland included a total of £1,430 million.</p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p /><p /> <p> </p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-09-21T12:58:36.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418497/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418497/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418497/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-11","Network Rail: Business Plans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate was made of the cost of Control Period 5 in (a) the initial industry plan published in September 2011 and (b) Network Rail's final strategic business plan.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","10036"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418498","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-21","<p>Network Rail have advised the Department that since the GWEP ECAM determination on the 12 September 2014, they have identified that the cost forecast will be higher. As part of Sir Peter Hendy’s review Network Rail intends to produce a revised baseline plan later in autumn 2015.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-09-21T12:51:46.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418498/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418498/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418498/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-11","Great Western Railway Line: Electrification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether the most recent cost estimate held by his Department for Great Western Main Line electrification is greater than the efficient cost estimate set by the Office of Rail and Road's Enhancement Cost Adjustment Mechanism on 12 September 2014.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","10035"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418499","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-21","<p>Yes. Directly Operated Railways are planning to publish their annual report and accounts for 2014/15 in October 2015.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-09-21T11:24:40.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418499/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418499/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418499/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-11","Directly Operated Railways","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether Directly Operated Railways will publish an annual report for 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","10026"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418500","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-21","<p>I announced the terms of the Direct Award with East Midlands Trains on 16 September.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-09-21T13:09:52.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418500/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418500/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418500/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-11","Midland Main Railway Line: Rolling Stock","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether the decision on rolling stock procurement for the Midland Main Line will be made by the direct award being negotiated with East Midlands Trains or the next franchise award.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","10032"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418501","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-21","<p>I have frequent meetings on a range of issues including rolling stock. We are committed to putting passengers first.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-09-21T12:35:41.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418501/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418501/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418501/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-11","Midland Main Railway Line: Rolling Stock","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent discussions he has had with East Midlands Trains and rolling stock companies on (a) extending the operational life of Intercity 125 trains operating on the Midland Main Line and making them compliant with the Disability Discrimination Act 1995 and (b) procuring new intercity rolling stock for operation on that line.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","10033"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418502","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-21","<p>The rolling stock market is a private sector one and Class 14X Pacer trains are owned by rolling stock companies. The Secretary of State has held no recent discussions with rail heritage organisations about the future of the Pacer trains.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-09-21T12:41:18.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418502/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418502/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418502/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-11","Rolling Stock","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent discussions he has had with rail heritage organisations on the future of the Class 14X series Pacer trains.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","10034"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418503","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-21","<p>The Department is working with Network Rail and First Great Western to appraise the case to increase the Oxford – Worcester train services to half-hourly and to reduce journey times.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-09-21T11:32:18.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418503/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418503/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418503/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-11","Oxford-Hereford Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent assessment he has made of the potential merits of double tracking the single track sections of the Cotswold Line.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","10027"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418504","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-21","<p>Some of the projects which make up the Great Western Route Modernisation have yet go through the ECAM process. But as the Hon Member is aware Sir Peter Hendy is currently reviewing the portfolio and will report back later in autumn.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-09-21T13:13:31.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418504/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418504/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418504/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-11","Great Western Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what his Department's estimate was of the cost of the Great Western Route Modernisation investment plan on the most recent date for which figures were available.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","10038"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418505","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-21","<p>The Secretary of State was notified that the Deep Alliance was being terminated and reshaped prior to the announcement on 12th June.　 This was a commercial decision for Network Rail and South West Trains to make.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-09-21T11:38:50.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418505/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418505/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418505/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-11","South West Trains","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he was consulted prior to Network Rail's decision to reshape the South West Trains Alliance announced on 12 June 2015.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","10028"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418506","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-21","<p>The Secretary of State has not received any formal request from Network Rail to increase its Control Period 5 borrowing facility limit since 4 July 2014.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-09-21T13:04:54.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418506/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418506/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418506/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-11","Network Rail: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether Network Rail has requested an increase to its CP5 borrowing facility limit since 4 July 2014.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","10037"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418507","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-21","<p>Network Rail has paused a small number of schemes where it makes sense to do so to avoid potentially abortive costs or planning applications, particularly where the cost estimate has increased significantly as in the case of Ely to Soham where work has identified that this project is far more complex than anticipated and so the estimated cost has more than trebled.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Ely to Soham double tracking work is one of a number of schemes which are needed to increase the number of freight trains which can run on the Felixstowe to Nuneaton route and a lot has been completed already. Network Rail has constructed a new section of railway at Nuneaton (Nuneaton North Chord), a new 1.2km stretch of track at Ipswich (Ipswich Chord) as well as various other pieces of work to re-model, re-signal and upgrade sections of the route between Felixstowe and Nuneaton.　 On its own therefore, the Ely to Soham doubling does not affect the number of freight trains which can operate.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-09-21T11:42:36.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418507/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418507/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418507/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-11","Railways: Freight","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the effect of Network Rail's decision to pause the Ely to Soham double tracking project on the forecast maximum number of freight trains per day that could be run on the Felixstowe to Nuneaton route by the end of Control Period 5.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","10029"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418508","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-21","<p>The Department did not receive a copy of Network Rail's Control Period 5 Business Plan Update on 31 March 2015. However, a letter from Mark Carne to Richard Price (the Chief Executive of Office of Rail and Road) on this subject was copied to the relevant official in the Department on that date.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-09-21T12:27:18.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418508/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418508/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418508/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-11","Network Rail: Business Plans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether his Department received a copy of Network Rail's Control Period 5 Business Plan Update on 31 March 2015.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","10031"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418509","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-21","<p>Network Rail carried out an extensive process involving the East West Rail Consortium and representatives from Train Operators to identify options for the scope of East West Rail Phase 2. This took into account the views of key stakeholders to identify the best options to take forward to a more detailed level of development. Network Rail have advised that they have now completed GRIP stage 2 and have begun consultations with local people and businesses prior to seeking the necessary powers to deliver the scheme.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-09-21T11:15:23.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418509/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418509/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418509/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-11","East-West Rail Link","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent assessment he has made of the effect of the time taken by Network Rail to reach GRIP 3 single option selection of the East West Rail Western Section Phase Two on the delivery timetable of that project.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","10025"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418510","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-21","<p>A process to update Control Period 5 plans for maintenance and renewals delivery is running in parallel with Sir Peter Hendy’s Control Period 5 Enhancements Re-planning Exercise.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-09-21T12:21:50.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418510/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418510/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418510/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-11","Network Rail: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether Sir Peter Hendy's review of Network Rail's investment programme is examining the company's maintenance and renewals spending plans for Control Period 5.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","10030"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418511","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-21","<p>The Department and the East West Rail Consortium are working with Network Rail to develop the business case for the central section. The two most promising route corridors are now being examined. The aim is to identify and appraise a single route option in time for the outcome to be included in the industry’s initial plan for Control Period 6.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-09-21T10:57:44.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418511/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418511/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418511/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-11","East-West Rail Link","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent discussions his Department has had with the East West Rail Consortium and Network Rail on the possible inclusion of the East West Rail Central Section in the industry's initial plans for Control Period 6.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","10024"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418512","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-16","<p>Between 2004-14 Network Rail achieved a cumulative improvement in efficiency of around 35-40% on operating, maintaining and renewing its network, as shown in Office of Rail and Road’s (ORR) Efficiency and Financial Assessments published for Control Periods 3 and 4.　 The ORR set Network Rail a challenging target of making efficiencies on top of those already achieved of 19.4% for the period 2014-19 (Control Period 5). The evidence base for this target included the McNulty Report as well as a significant amount of top-down benchmarking, bottom-up analysis and studies.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>On train services, this Government is focused on maximising value for money for taxpayers and rail users. Since the relaunch of the franchising programme in 2013, each franchise has been subject to a detailed process of scrutiny, ensuring both that the benefits for taxpayers are realised and that the process maximises efficiencies. The success of the process in securing efficiencies of the type envisaged by McNulty is demonstrated by every successful bid achieving a better price than was originally envisaged by the Department, with consequential considerable benefits for the taxpayer.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-09-16T14:56:29.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418512/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418512/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418512/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-11","Rail Value for Money Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what progress his Department and Network Rail have made on meeting the rail industry efficiency targets of the McNulty Report.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","10081"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418513","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-16","<p>No Department for Transport officials have attended any meetings of Network Rail's Major Projects Delivery sub-committee, Critical Infrastructure sub-committee or Business Plan sub-committee since 22 January 2015. However, officials from the Shareholder Executive attended eleven meetings of the Major Projects Delivery Committee in that time to observe, in order improve mutual understanding between Network Rail and the Government.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-09-16T15:08:34.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418513/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418513/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/418513/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-11","Network Rail","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether officials in his Department have attended any meetings of Network Rail's (a) Major Projects Delivery sub-committee, (b) Critical Infrastructure sub-committee and (c) Business Plan sub-committee since 22 January 2015.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","10082"
